00:05:25.570 --> 00:05:27.250
In the past few
hours, we have heard

00:05:27.250 --> 00:05:30.340
moving testimony about
the legacy of slavery

00:05:30.340 --> 00:05:32.530
at American universities.

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:34.940
We've heard about colleges
buying and selling

00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:37.540
enslaved workers,
about students bringing

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:40.170
their enslaved servants
to their campuses,

00:05:40.170 --> 00:05:42.580
about presidents,
faculties, alumni

00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:46.060
and donors of these
institutions as slaveholders,

00:05:46.060 --> 00:05:48.910
about how enslaved
construction workers built

00:05:48.910 --> 00:05:52.240
the physical infrastructure
of various universities,

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:55.510
and how the huge stream of
money derived from the slave

00:05:55.510 --> 00:05:59.020
economy infused institutions
of higher learning

00:05:59.020 --> 00:06:01.390
and enabled them,
among other things,

00:06:01.390 --> 00:06:04.510
to train an elite that
legitimated notions

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:07.150
of racial difference
and enslavement

00:06:07.150 --> 00:06:11.190
and enforced the institutions
that had enabled them.

00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:14.110
A little more than
260 years ago,

00:06:14.110 --> 00:06:17.740
it was three Harvard
University-trained judges

00:06:17.740 --> 00:06:21.040
who convicted Phyllis, an
enslaved worker accused

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:25.330
of killing her master, to be
burned at the stake just a few

00:06:25.330 --> 00:06:30.410
hundred yards away from where
we are meeting right now.

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:33.320
This story and many
others are moving,

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:35.400
and they are disturbing.

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:39.330
We can see that some
of our most esteemed

00:06:39.330 --> 00:06:42.060
educational
institutions are also

00:06:42.060 --> 00:06:46.080
the product of some of the most
horrific violence that has ever

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:49.680
descended upon any
group of people.

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:52.770
Yes, we did know that much
of the wealth of the American

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:55.560
South had been
built upon slavery,

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:59.040
that its roads, its canals,
its plantations, and its cities

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:01.680
were the result of the
exploitation of millions

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:04.190
of African-Americans.

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:06.980
But today at this
conference, we learned

00:07:06.980 --> 00:07:10.730
that the centers of higher
learning, of debate,

00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:12.590
of the great
humanistic traditions

00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:16.130
of the Western world, of
our cherished enlightenment

00:07:16.130 --> 00:07:21.410
traditions, were also built at
least partly upon the violence

00:07:21.410 --> 00:07:24.980
of the slave trader, the
Middle Passage, the auction

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:28.470
block, and the whip.

00:07:28.470 --> 00:07:32.150
We are rightly disturbed
by these histories,

00:07:32.150 --> 00:07:35.720
but if we sit back and think
about the broader context,

00:07:35.720 --> 00:07:38.480
we should not be too
surprised that slavery

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:42.020
was central to the institutions
of higher education

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:45.490
as they emerged
in North America.

00:07:45.490 --> 00:07:47.740
After all, for
several centuries,

00:07:47.740 --> 00:07:51.410
North America was part of the
great belt of slave plantation

00:07:51.410 --> 00:07:53.770
economies that stretched
from South America

00:07:53.770 --> 00:07:55.990
through the
Caribbean all the way

00:07:55.990 --> 00:07:59.180
to the borders of New Jersey.

00:07:59.180 --> 00:08:01.910
Yet here in Boston,
and here at Harvard,

00:08:01.910 --> 00:08:05.600
the story of slavery that has
been told for all too long

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:07.070
is different.

00:08:07.070 --> 00:08:09.680
New England is hailed
in the national memory

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:13.460
as a place of freedom, a place
where religious dissenters

00:08:13.460 --> 00:08:16.520
settled on the stony
soils of New England

00:08:16.520 --> 00:08:21.310
to create a new world
of liberty and freedom.

00:08:21.310 --> 00:08:24.730
And thus, if we look at the
history of the institutions

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:28.960
of higher learning, including
the history of Harvard,

00:08:28.960 --> 00:08:31.870
we have taught this
history, and they

00:08:31.870 --> 00:08:34.360
have taught these
histories about themselves,

00:08:34.360 --> 00:08:38.260
as exactly this story, as
a story of the expansion

00:08:38.260 --> 00:08:39.460
of human freedom.

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:43.039
Or at least they have
done so until recently.

00:08:43.039 --> 00:08:45.010
When I first embarked
upon the project

00:08:45.010 --> 00:08:47.890
of trying to understand
the historical relationship

00:08:47.890 --> 00:08:51.250
between Harvard University
and slavery with my students,

00:08:51.250 --> 00:08:53.350
the literature on the
history of Harvard

00:08:53.350 --> 00:08:57.320
was almost silent on
the question of slavery.

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:00.620
And when the students began to
uncover a different history,

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:05.480
they and others who listened
to them were surprised.

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:08.510
Yet in retrospect, it seems
that the only thing that

00:09:08.510 --> 00:09:12.230
should surprise us
was our surprise

00:09:12.230 --> 00:09:16.430
and that it took us so long
for us to allow ourselves to be

00:09:16.430 --> 00:09:18.980
surprised by that history.

00:09:18.980 --> 00:09:22.340
After all, a whole range
of studies, many of them

00:09:22.340 --> 00:09:25.910
quite old, had argued
for the continental reach

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:27.800
and the importance of slavery.

00:09:27.800 --> 00:09:31.280
People such as Eric Williams and
WEB Du Bois and Ronald Bailey,

00:09:31.280 --> 00:09:33.410
among many others,
had powerfully

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:37.650
argued for the nationwide or
even global reach of slavery.

00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:41.000
And it would have been unlikely
that the oldest university

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.370
in North America
would not in some ways

00:09:43.370 --> 00:09:48.690
be also involved in that
story of slavery as well.

00:09:48.690 --> 00:09:52.440
In dusty archival records,
countless published volumes

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:55.980
in the libraries, and by careful
study of Harvard's oldest

00:09:55.980 --> 00:09:59.220
buildings and neighboring
colonial graveyards, students

00:09:59.220 --> 00:10:03.850
uncovered many links
between Harvard and slavery.

00:10:03.850 --> 00:10:06.130
They chronicled how
Harvard presidents

00:10:06.130 --> 00:10:11.310
brought enslaved workers to
live with them on campus.

00:10:11.310 --> 00:10:14.940
They analyzed how significant
gifts to the university

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:19.690
were drawn from the
exploitation of slave labor.

00:10:19.690 --> 00:10:22.980
They found evidence for some
of Harvard's endowment invested

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:27.450
in merchant voyages related
to the slave economy.

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:29.970
They showed how
Harvard's administration

00:10:29.970 --> 00:10:32.910
favored the suppression
of public debates

00:10:32.910 --> 00:10:36.750
on [? slavering, ?] fearing a
backlash from the local Boston

00:10:36.750 --> 00:10:38.400
elite.

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:41.190
Harvard-trained judges
condemned an enslaved woman,

00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:44.325
as we just heard, to be burned
on the stake just a few hundred

00:10:44.325 --> 00:10:46.840
yards away from here.

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:49.820
The students charted how
the sons of Southern slave

00:10:49.820 --> 00:10:52.310
owners who returned
after college

00:10:52.310 --> 00:10:55.670
to a lifetime of violent
mastery over their workers

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:59.510
mingled on campus with the
sons of the Northern elites,

00:10:59.510 --> 00:11:04.940
forging networks that
often lasted a lifetime.

00:11:04.940 --> 00:11:08.510
The students traced the
history of Antiguan planter

00:11:08.510 --> 00:11:12.630
who became a major funder
of the Harvard Law School.

00:11:12.630 --> 00:11:14.430
More generally,
the students show

00:11:14.430 --> 00:11:18.000
how the deep immersion of
Boston's merchant community

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.690
with the plantation
economy of the Caribbean,

00:11:21.690 --> 00:11:25.380
yielded resources
for the university.

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:28.770
They analyzed how Harvard
acquired one of Cuba's largest

00:11:28.770 --> 00:11:33.060
sugar plantations, a plantation
whose owner, Ed Atkins,

00:11:33.060 --> 00:11:36.380
provided resources for
the university to draw on.

00:11:36.380 --> 00:11:39.180
And these resources were
derived from the labor

00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:41.760
of his enslaved workers.

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:43.710
And students were
also able to show

00:11:43.710 --> 00:11:48.300
how the development of some of
the most viciously racist ideas

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:53.290
were spearheaded by the
members of the Harvard faculty.

00:11:53.290 --> 00:11:55.840
Indeed, what the
students found was

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:58.150
that Harvard's
connection to slavery

00:11:58.150 --> 00:12:00.970
extended beyond the
abolition of slavery

00:12:00.970 --> 00:12:03.790
in Massachusetts in
the 1780s, and it even

00:12:03.790 --> 00:12:07.510
extended beyond the abolition
of slavery in the United States

00:12:07.510 --> 00:12:10.950
in 1865.

00:12:10.950 --> 00:12:13.770
In the process of
doing this research

00:12:13.770 --> 00:12:17.190
students have made
a larger point.

00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:20.010
They have shown that
the history of slavery

00:12:20.010 --> 00:12:23.850
is the history of the
nation as a whole.

00:12:23.850 --> 00:12:25.980
Even in acknowledging
the crimes of slavery,

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:29.460
we have all too often settled
into a seemingly comfortable

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:33.870
fiction that slavery was a
regional institution, confined

00:12:33.870 --> 00:12:37.380
by the 19th century to the
states of the American South,

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:39.840
with Northerners
principally involved

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:43.610
with slavery by bringing
about its abolition.

00:12:43.610 --> 00:12:46.430
Slavery, in fact, appears
as limited in scope,

00:12:46.430 --> 00:12:51.470
an unfortunate detour on the
nation's march to modernity,

00:12:51.470 --> 00:12:56.950
and certainly not as one of the
engines of America's economy.

00:12:56.950 --> 00:12:59.680
But as the students
have shown, slavery

00:12:59.680 --> 00:13:04.090
was not a regional institution
or a regional problem.

00:13:04.090 --> 00:13:08.290
Slavery was everywhere, in
the merchant houses of Boston,

00:13:08.290 --> 00:13:12.070
the banks of New York, the
factories of Rhode Island,

00:13:12.070 --> 00:13:16.830
and the universities
throughout New England.

00:13:16.830 --> 00:13:20.880
Such recognition of the
continent-spanning importance

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:25.440
of slavery, in turn, also gives
a much greater appreciation

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:28.530
for those Americans who had
the courage and the resolve

00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:31.770
to stand up against
slavery, among them

00:13:31.770 --> 00:13:34.800
members of the
Harvard community,

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:36.750
and for those
Americans who would

00:13:36.750 --> 00:13:39.120
die in battle
during the Civil War

00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:42.120
to bring about emancipation,
among them also

00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:45.550
members of the
Harvard community.

00:13:45.550 --> 00:13:48.490
Recognizing the
power of slavery,

00:13:48.490 --> 00:13:51.160
including the power
of slavery at Harvard,

00:13:51.160 --> 00:13:53.290
does put into much
sharper relief

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:57.520
the courage and dedication
of those, black and white,

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:00.700
who fought against slavery.

00:14:00.700 --> 00:14:04.480
They stood against some of
the most powerful interests

00:14:04.480 --> 00:14:05.635
of their own times.

00:14:08.610 --> 00:14:13.480
As historians and as
members of this community,

00:14:13.480 --> 00:14:16.390
our first commitment
is to uncovering

00:14:16.390 --> 00:14:19.550
the historical truth.

00:14:19.550 --> 00:14:23.150
Part of that truth is
the deep entanglement

00:14:23.150 --> 00:14:27.440
of this institution with
slavery and also with some

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:30.770
of the racism, exploitation,
and repression that

00:14:30.770 --> 00:14:35.650
descended upon
African-Americans after slavery.

00:14:35.650 --> 00:14:38.860
This history is inscribed
in this institution,

00:14:38.860 --> 00:14:42.620
and it is also inscribed
in the nation as a whole.

00:14:42.620 --> 00:14:45.280
The economic,
cultural, ideological,

00:14:45.280 --> 00:14:48.310
and political legacy of
slavery and its aftermath

00:14:48.310 --> 00:14:50.600
is with us today.

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:52.660
It is not just history.

00:14:52.660 --> 00:14:53.920
It is our present.

00:14:53.920 --> 00:14:56.460
Slavery is our present.

00:14:56.460 --> 00:14:59.490
As members of this
university and as members

00:14:59.490 --> 00:15:02.070
of our national
community, we need

00:15:02.070 --> 00:15:04.440
to confront these histories.

00:15:04.440 --> 00:15:08.220
We cannot successfully move
forward as a university,

00:15:08.220 --> 00:15:12.420
as a nation, or as citizens
without acknowledging this

00:15:12.420 --> 00:15:16.320
history and making it
important to the understanding

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:18.580
of our present.

00:15:18.580 --> 00:15:21.920
And to be meaningful,
that acknowledgement

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:25.310
will have to have economic
and political consequences.

00:15:25.310 --> 00:15:29.060
It cannot be purely
symbolic or rhetorical.

00:15:29.060 --> 00:15:29.887
Thank you.

00:15:29.887 --> 00:15:33.366
[APPLAUSE]

00:15:48.780 --> 00:15:51.140
- Hello, everyone, and
thank you so much again

00:15:51.140 --> 00:15:52.940
for the introductions.

00:15:52.940 --> 00:15:55.560
My presentation
today has two parts.

00:15:55.560 --> 00:15:57.530
First, I will quickly
introduce myself

00:15:57.530 --> 00:16:00.920
and my association with the
Harvard and Slavery Project.

00:16:00.920 --> 00:16:03.470
And second, I will take
you through an example

00:16:03.470 --> 00:16:05.900
of some scholarship on
Harvard and slavery,

00:16:05.900 --> 00:16:08.810
which is the findings of
my senior thesis, entitled

00:16:08.810 --> 00:16:13.040
Plantation University:
Harvard Scientists at Soledad

00:16:13.040 --> 00:16:13.916
Plantation--

00:16:13.916 --> 00:16:16.040
I'm sorry, Harvard Scientists
at Soledad Plantation

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:19.010
and Cuba's Transition from
Slavery to Free Labor,

00:16:19.010 --> 00:16:20.930
1880 to 1920.

00:16:20.930 --> 00:16:22.392
And as my presentation
will go on,

00:16:22.392 --> 00:16:24.350
and looking at this thesis
several years later,

00:16:24.350 --> 00:16:27.920
I realize 1920 is actually not
a great time to cut this off.

00:16:27.920 --> 00:16:30.720
The connection actually
extends much further than that.

00:16:33.950 --> 00:16:37.100
So, to start, my
name is Alexa Rahman,

00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:38.600
and I'm currently
a doctoral student

00:16:38.600 --> 00:16:40.310
at Harvard Business
School, studying

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:43.610
accounting, management, and
corporate accountability.

00:16:43.610 --> 00:16:46.280
I got involved in this field
when I took Professor Beckert's

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:48.710
Harvard and Slavery
research seminar when

00:16:48.710 --> 00:16:52.310
I was a freshman at
Harvard College in 2009.

00:16:52.310 --> 00:16:53.980
I was interested in
this class because I

00:16:53.980 --> 00:16:56.300
had heard of
historians discovering

00:16:56.300 --> 00:16:59.060
other links between
slavery and universities

00:16:59.060 --> 00:17:00.800
at our peer schools like Brown.

00:17:00.800 --> 00:17:04.310
And I was curious to see if
we at Harvard had similar ties

00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:08.510
to the history of slavery that
we simply didn't know about.

00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:10.670
My research focused
on a research facility

00:17:10.670 --> 00:17:13.490
that Harvard maintained on
a sugar plantation named

00:17:13.490 --> 00:17:18.170
Soledad in Cuba in the late
1800s to the mid 1900s.

00:17:18.170 --> 00:17:21.230
That facility, called the
Harvard Botanic Station,

00:17:21.230 --> 00:17:22.880
was created by the
two figures that you

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:25.760
can see here on this slide.

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:29.630
Edwin Atkins, to the left, was
a prominent Boston businessman,

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:32.300
West Indian sugar
merchant, and slave owner,

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:36.520
who purchased Soledad
Plantation in 1884.

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:41.970
Oakes Ames, to the right, was
a Harvard professor of botany.

00:17:41.970 --> 00:17:46.190
In the aftermath of Cuban
slave emancipation in 1886,

00:17:46.190 --> 00:17:49.010
Atkins wished to apply the
latest scientific knowledge

00:17:49.010 --> 00:17:52.220
in agricultural engineering
to boost production

00:17:52.220 --> 00:17:54.350
at Soledad Plantation.

00:17:54.350 --> 00:17:57.560
In 1899, he collaborated
with Professor Ames

00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:00.530
to develop the Harvard
Botanic Station at Soledad

00:18:00.530 --> 00:18:04.140
to conduct research on sugarcane
to support his business.

00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:06.920
This relationship, I
argue in my thesis,

00:18:06.920 --> 00:18:09.770
would forge a profitable
but problematic link

00:18:09.770 --> 00:18:11.900
between the history of
Harvard and the history

00:18:11.900 --> 00:18:14.620
of Caribbean slavery.

00:18:14.620 --> 00:18:17.230
My thesis makes
three main arguments.

00:18:17.230 --> 00:18:19.330
First, it contends
that by accepting gifts

00:18:19.330 --> 00:18:22.060
from Edwin Atkins in
the early 20th century,

00:18:22.060 --> 00:18:25.180
Harvard used wealth and land
accumulated by slave labor

00:18:25.180 --> 00:18:27.340
as scholarly resources.

00:18:27.340 --> 00:18:29.950
This follows from evidence
that Atkins's family wealth

00:18:29.950 --> 00:18:33.340
was dependent on the West
Indian slave economy.

00:18:33.340 --> 00:18:35.890
Second, it argues that
the social and business

00:18:35.890 --> 00:18:39.760
ties between Atkins
and Harvard personnel

00:18:39.760 --> 00:18:42.160
resulted in significant
financial donations

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:46.420
to the institution, which drew
on the Atkins family fortune.

00:18:46.420 --> 00:18:48.220
Lastly, and perhaps
most important,

00:18:48.220 --> 00:18:51.580
it asserts that Edwin Atkins's
construction of the Harvard

00:18:51.580 --> 00:18:55.510
Botanic Station at Soledad
provided a significant gift

00:18:55.510 --> 00:18:57.430
to the university's
academic assets.

00:19:00.500 --> 00:19:02.660
I'll begin by just
providing a short background

00:19:02.660 --> 00:19:05.660
on the sources of Edwin Atkins's
personal wealth, which he later

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:08.450
used to finance
Harvard researchers.

00:19:08.450 --> 00:19:11.240
During the 19th century,
the Atkins family,

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:14.210
based in Belmont,
Massachusetts, rose to riches

00:19:14.210 --> 00:19:16.790
by trading goods
manufactured by slaves,

00:19:16.790 --> 00:19:20.090
mainly sugar and molasses,
in the West Indies.

00:19:20.090 --> 00:19:22.610
When Edwin Atkins took
over the family business,

00:19:22.610 --> 00:19:24.800
he assumed ownership
of the Soledad sugar

00:19:24.800 --> 00:19:32.300
plantation, a 900-acre refinery
with approximately 177 slaves.

00:19:32.300 --> 00:19:35.510
Cuban slave
emancipation in 1886,

00:19:35.510 --> 00:19:37.760
as I mentioned
previously, coincided

00:19:37.760 --> 00:19:39.470
with a period of
major innovations

00:19:39.470 --> 00:19:42.620
in industrial production
technology, which also included

00:19:42.620 --> 00:19:45.060
agricultural engineering.

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:47.720
Other innovations, such as
steam powered refineries,

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:50.090
rail transport, and
cable communication all

00:19:50.090 --> 00:19:52.490
transformed the sugar
production business

00:19:52.490 --> 00:19:54.560
just as the country
was beginning to shift

00:19:54.560 --> 00:19:57.600
from slave labor to free labor.

00:19:57.600 --> 00:20:00.350
Atkins, eager to keep
up with his competitors,

00:20:00.350 --> 00:20:03.200
invested heavily in new
production technologies

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:05.720
and approached Harvard
professor Ames precisely

00:20:05.720 --> 00:20:07.520
to help his business
successfully

00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:10.730
navigate this transition
from slave production

00:20:10.730 --> 00:20:12.454
to mechanized production.

00:20:16.410 --> 00:20:18.900
Drawing on his Cuban
fortune, Atkins

00:20:18.900 --> 00:20:22.800
made significant donations
of cash, scholarships,

00:20:22.800 --> 00:20:27.900
and academic resources to
Harvard from 1899 to 1925,

00:20:27.900 --> 00:20:30.690
enabling students and
professors to conduct research

00:20:30.690 --> 00:20:33.870
on improving the quality
and yield of tropical plants

00:20:33.870 --> 00:20:35.640
such as sugarcane.

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:42.150
His largest single donation,
which was $17,119 in 1919,

00:20:42.150 --> 00:20:44.490
was to establish the
Atkins Fund for Tropical

00:20:44.490 --> 00:20:46.710
Research in Economic Botany.

00:20:46.710 --> 00:20:49.080
This gift would be worth a
little over half a million

00:20:49.080 --> 00:20:51.630
dollars today.

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:54.660
Physical research spaces like
the Harvard Botanic Station

00:20:54.660 --> 00:20:57.120
helped transport
intellectual power

00:20:57.120 --> 00:20:59.940
from the halls of academia
and apply it directly

00:20:59.940 --> 00:21:02.280
to issues on the plantation.

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:04.710
Ames and Atkins's
partnership culminated

00:21:04.710 --> 00:21:08.730
in 1925, when they constructed
the official Harvard

00:21:08.730 --> 00:21:12.810
House, a boarding house with
bedrooms and a laboratory space

00:21:12.810 --> 00:21:16.140
for Harvard students to conduct
research at the plantation

00:21:16.140 --> 00:21:18.360
under the management
of the university.

00:21:18.360 --> 00:21:21.420
And what you see here is an
image from the inside of one

00:21:21.420 --> 00:21:25.740
of those labs in 1930
on the plantation.

00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:29.820
In recognition of Atkins's
long and profitable patronage,

00:21:29.820 --> 00:21:31.440
Harvard president
Charles Elliott

00:21:31.440 --> 00:21:34.110
even awarded Atkins
an honorary degree

00:21:34.110 --> 00:21:39.660
at the 1903 commencement.

00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:42.880
So, although slavery
ended in 1886,

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:46.600
the physical, cultural, and
ideological legacy of slavery

00:21:46.600 --> 00:21:48.580
remained palpable
to Harvard scholars

00:21:48.580 --> 00:21:51.580
as they continued to
conduct research at Soledad.

00:21:51.580 --> 00:21:54.610
To emphasize this point I've
included a quote from a letter

00:21:54.610 --> 00:21:57.610
that Professor Ames wrote on
one of his research visits

00:21:57.610 --> 00:22:00.460
to the plantation.

00:22:00.460 --> 00:22:03.160
He writes, "The slave
bell on the plantation

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:06.970
rang out one single,
musical, but dull note.

00:22:06.970 --> 00:22:09.970
And I really felt that
all the cruelty of slavery

00:22:09.970 --> 00:22:12.900
was summoned in
that one bell tone.

00:22:12.900 --> 00:22:14.520
My subsequent
thoughts were perhaps

00:22:14.520 --> 00:22:17.670
similar to those of some
compassionate creature, who

00:22:17.670 --> 00:22:20.010
suddenly awakened
in days gone by,

00:22:20.010 --> 00:22:23.490
to the atrocities of holding
in bondage one's fellow man,

00:22:23.490 --> 00:22:25.560
and driving him to
and from his work

00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:28.080
by the note of a
doleful bell, aided

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:30.750
by this stinging lash,
which injures one far

00:22:30.750 --> 00:22:34.750
deeper than steel or bronze."

00:22:34.750 --> 00:22:36.490
And I should add this isn't--

00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:39.280
I didn't include the rest
of the letter on the slide,

00:22:39.280 --> 00:22:41.590
but it's interesting
that he doesn't actually

00:22:41.590 --> 00:22:44.860
go on to address that
this is a problem.

00:22:44.860 --> 00:22:48.760
He goes on to talk about how
this is a issue that people

00:22:48.760 --> 00:22:51.030
must have faced a long
time ago and isn't

00:22:51.030 --> 00:22:53.740
antiquity fascinating.

00:22:53.740 --> 00:22:56.800
This was written like about 20
years after the end of slavery.

00:22:56.800 --> 00:22:59.650
And he was working
for the slave-owner

00:22:59.650 --> 00:23:01.445
who perpetrated these crimes.

00:23:01.445 --> 00:23:02.320
So, just interesting.

00:23:02.320 --> 00:23:04.960
I know we had talked
earlier about people back

00:23:04.960 --> 00:23:07.330
then maybe didn't realize
it was a bad thing.

00:23:07.330 --> 00:23:10.960
This is an example of someone
recognizing it and willfully

00:23:10.960 --> 00:23:13.240
ignoring it.

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:14.980
So, despite these
mixed feelings,

00:23:14.980 --> 00:23:17.265
apparently, about
working at Soledad,

00:23:17.265 --> 00:23:19.960
Ames visited his
facilities in Cuba often,

00:23:19.960 --> 00:23:23.770
bringing back data to supplement
his science classes at Harvard.

00:23:23.770 --> 00:23:25.360
Students and
instructors continued

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:27.640
to use the site for
decades to come,

00:23:27.640 --> 00:23:30.370
leaving behind a trail
of photographs, sketches,

00:23:30.370 --> 00:23:34.200
and Crimson articles documenting
their time at the plantation.

00:23:34.200 --> 00:23:36.910
The university maintained
control of the research

00:23:36.910 --> 00:23:39.610
facilities until
travel became difficult

00:23:39.610 --> 00:23:41.940
during the communist
Cuban revolution.

00:23:41.940 --> 00:23:44.140
And the last director
of the Harvard station

00:23:44.140 --> 00:23:50.320
left the island in 1961.

00:23:50.320 --> 00:23:52.540
So, to summarize,
my thesis argued

00:23:52.540 --> 00:23:56.170
that Atkins's donations of
funds and academic resources

00:23:56.170 --> 00:23:59.770
sprang from wealth and lands
directly dependent on profits

00:23:59.770 --> 00:24:01.930
from trading West
Indian slave products

00:24:01.930 --> 00:24:04.870
and eventually owning
Soledad Plantation.

00:24:04.870 --> 00:24:08.080
Harvard benefited from
the Atkins's fortune

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:11.170
by accepting financial
and educational gifts,

00:24:11.170 --> 00:24:13.940
in operating Ames's
very own Harvard Botanic

00:24:13.940 --> 00:24:18.100
Station for over half a century
on the very grounds of Soledad

00:24:18.100 --> 00:24:19.810
Plantation.

00:24:19.810 --> 00:24:23.020
The images on this slide
illustrate Harvard professors

00:24:23.020 --> 00:24:26.950
harvesting papayas on
the station in 1924,

00:24:26.950 --> 00:24:29.920
as well as an image of a
sign bearing Harvard's name

00:24:29.920 --> 00:24:34.610
that was found at the
plantation in 2005.

00:24:34.610 --> 00:24:36.710
In conclusion, I
believe these findings

00:24:36.710 --> 00:24:39.470
demonstrate the importance
of investigating connections

00:24:39.470 --> 00:24:41.540
between Harvard and slavery.

00:24:41.540 --> 00:24:44.780
I hope that this research will
allow us to better understand

00:24:44.780 --> 00:24:47.210
and recognize how the
history of slavery

00:24:47.210 --> 00:24:49.760
has contributed to the
development of our school's

00:24:49.760 --> 00:24:54.260
vast educational resources,
which we still enjoy today.

00:24:54.260 --> 00:24:54.760
Thank you.

00:24:54.760 --> 00:24:58.211
[APPLAUSE]

