00:26:39.470 --> 00:26:40.390
And so, this is a--

00:26:40.390 --> 00:26:44.560
we believe that thanks to this
project, Harvard Law School

00:26:44.560 --> 00:26:47.950
is one of the best documented
of all institutions of higher

00:26:47.950 --> 00:26:49.730
learning in the United States.

00:26:49.730 --> 00:26:54.460
Now you may ask, well,
why is that important?

00:26:54.460 --> 00:26:58.120
I have to be very sensitive
here and not arrogant.

00:26:58.120 --> 00:27:00.880
We have neighbors to the
south in New Haven that

00:27:00.880 --> 00:27:04.070
are overly sensitive
about their law school,

00:27:04.070 --> 00:27:07.630
and even though it's
younger and much smaller.

00:27:07.630 --> 00:27:12.190
And-- but the truth
is, for good or bad,

00:27:12.190 --> 00:27:16.420
Harvard Law School is the
most powerful law school,

00:27:16.420 --> 00:27:17.710
historically, in America.

00:27:17.710 --> 00:27:21.210
And it remains-- just count
the Supreme Court justices--

00:27:21.210 --> 00:27:23.892
it remains the most powerful.

00:27:23.892 --> 00:27:25.100
That wasn't arrogant, was it?

00:27:25.100 --> 00:27:28.150
No, just facts, just facts.

00:27:28.150 --> 00:27:32.090
Now, we knew that On
the Battlefield of Merit

00:27:32.090 --> 00:27:33.340
was going to be controversial.

00:27:33.340 --> 00:27:34.960
I mean, we knew.

00:27:34.960 --> 00:27:39.700
And the things that
we were prepared for

00:27:39.700 --> 00:27:42.460
was, first, the research
on the Civil War.

00:27:42.460 --> 00:27:46.930
Harvard Law School was
next only to West Point

00:27:46.930 --> 00:27:50.370
the leading source of military
officers for the Confederacy--

00:27:50.370 --> 00:27:55.570
13 major generals, 60 colonels
of Southern regiments.

00:27:55.570 --> 00:27:57.610
Almost as many Harvard
Law School students

00:27:57.610 --> 00:28:02.110
died fighting for slavery as
died fighting against slavery.

00:28:02.110 --> 00:28:04.240
And that was because
during the entire period

00:28:04.240 --> 00:28:07.540
of the 1840s and
1850s, Joseph Story,

00:28:07.540 --> 00:28:09.640
Simon Greenleaf recruited--

00:28:09.640 --> 00:28:11.890
to make a national law
school by recruiting

00:28:11.890 --> 00:28:13.390
in Georgia, Atlanta and--

00:28:13.390 --> 00:28:17.680
in Atlanta and in
Savannah and Charleston.

00:28:17.680 --> 00:28:19.750
So, we knew about that.

00:28:19.750 --> 00:28:23.090
We also knew that
Christopher Columbus

00:28:23.090 --> 00:28:27.910
Langdell and his disciples
were fervently anti-feminist.

00:28:27.910 --> 00:28:32.500
We knew that they had
instilled a gender apartheid

00:28:32.500 --> 00:28:36.670
system at the school
which lasted until 1950.

00:28:36.670 --> 00:28:39.730
No women were admitted at
Harvard Law School until 1950.

00:28:39.730 --> 00:28:43.330
I've talked to many
in the first class.

00:28:43.330 --> 00:28:46.780
No women on the
faculty until 1971.

00:28:46.780 --> 00:28:49.210
Now, I've talked to all of them.

00:28:49.210 --> 00:28:53.950
So, this is-- there's
plenty of controversy there.

00:28:53.950 --> 00:28:56.830
But what really got
the students excited,

00:28:56.830 --> 00:29:03.220
and in retrospect, I
should've seen this coming, is

00:29:03.220 --> 00:29:06.400
the establishment of Harvard
Law School as a foundation

00:29:06.400 --> 00:29:08.437
based on slavery.

00:29:08.437 --> 00:29:09.520
There's no doubt about it.

00:29:09.520 --> 00:29:12.970
We knew, we knew early
on that Isaac Royall--

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:17.950
this is a portrayal of him
at age 24 with his wife

00:29:17.950 --> 00:29:21.130
and sister-in-law
and daughters--

00:29:21.130 --> 00:29:23.110
he was a slave owner.

00:29:23.110 --> 00:29:27.100
We knew he had 20,
24 slaves in Medford.

00:29:27.100 --> 00:29:31.840
What we did not know was
that Royall's fortune

00:29:31.840 --> 00:29:36.190
was based on the Antiguan
sugar plantations.

00:29:36.190 --> 00:29:39.880
The cruelty of those
plantations was beyond belief.

00:29:39.880 --> 00:29:44.250
He owned 180 slaves with
his father on Antigua

00:29:44.250 --> 00:29:45.570
in the Popes Head region.

00:29:48.730 --> 00:29:52.550
Sugar slavery was very cruel.

00:29:52.550 --> 00:29:55.000
They issued the slaves
knives, the enslaved people

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:56.320
knives every morning.

00:29:56.320 --> 00:29:58.020
They had numbers
on them because you

00:29:58.020 --> 00:30:00.520
had to turn the
knives in every night.

00:30:00.520 --> 00:30:03.260
And they were razor sharp.

00:30:03.260 --> 00:30:07.240
A single nick without
antibiotic and death

00:30:07.240 --> 00:30:09.610
was almost inevitable.

00:30:09.610 --> 00:30:12.460
The casualty rate
on these plantations

00:30:12.460 --> 00:30:17.230
was extremely, extremely high.

00:30:17.230 --> 00:30:20.310
The only reason
why Harvard School

00:30:20.310 --> 00:30:22.830
is going to have
its bicentennial,

00:30:22.830 --> 00:30:26.820
and it's going to be the oldest
school, law school in America,

00:30:26.820 --> 00:30:33.360
is because the fortune that
Royall made in Antiguan sugar

00:30:33.360 --> 00:30:38.700
was left in a bequest
in 1788 to Harvard

00:30:38.700 --> 00:30:41.190
to establish a law professor.

00:30:41.190 --> 00:30:44.040
The Royall Professorship
is one of the oldest

00:30:44.040 --> 00:30:45.390
chairs at Harvard.

00:30:45.390 --> 00:30:47.310
It's occupied right now
with great distinction

00:30:47.310 --> 00:30:50.280
by Janet Halley, who
in her inauguration

00:30:50.280 --> 00:30:55.730
gave tribute to the slaves
on which the chair is based.

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:57.960
But, you know it's--

00:30:57.960 --> 00:31:01.560
as we got into
this, it got worse.

00:31:01.560 --> 00:31:06.690
There was a major slave revolt
on the Royall plantation.

00:31:09.270 --> 00:31:11.820
The revolt was
under a leadership

00:31:11.820 --> 00:31:14.595
of a man, very brave
man, named King Court.

00:31:17.550 --> 00:31:19.920
Unfortunately for them,
it was betrayed just

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:22.350
at the last moment.

00:31:22.350 --> 00:31:27.120
There are only 27
white men on the island

00:31:27.120 --> 00:31:28.770
capable carrying gun.

00:31:28.770 --> 00:31:31.540
One was Isaac Royall.

00:31:31.540 --> 00:31:34.440
There were 364 slaves.

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:37.200
But they-- white
men had the guns.

00:31:37.200 --> 00:31:40.800
The uprising was betrayed,
it was suppressed,

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:49.470
and as a result, 77 enslaved
people were burned at the stake

00:31:49.470 --> 00:31:52.440
by Royall and his friends.

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:54.600
They also-- the six leaders--

00:31:54.600 --> 00:32:00.670
were drawn and quartered, and
King Court was gibbeted alive.

00:32:00.670 --> 00:32:04.080
So, this gentleman
here, who founded

00:32:04.080 --> 00:32:08.310
the Harvard Law School's
chair, which became

00:32:08.310 --> 00:32:09.920
the center of the new school--

00:32:09.920 --> 00:32:12.360
as his, one of his
descendants said,

00:32:12.360 --> 00:32:13.890
I know he was a slave owner.

00:32:13.890 --> 00:32:15.980
I hope he was a
nice slave owner.

00:32:15.980 --> 00:32:17.850
And he wasn't a
nice slave owner.

00:32:17.850 --> 00:32:21.210
This was a brutal slave owner.

00:32:21.210 --> 00:32:23.260
Here's his house in Medford.

00:32:23.260 --> 00:32:26.220
It's right, you know, 20
minutes drive from here.

00:32:26.220 --> 00:32:28.560
Now that's the slave block.

00:32:28.560 --> 00:32:32.520
The reason why he
came to Medford

00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:34.140
was because of fear
of yellow fever,

00:32:34.140 --> 00:32:37.480
but also fear of
another slave revolt.

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:39.390
He brought about
20 slaves with him.

00:32:39.390 --> 00:32:41.380
They lived in this block.

00:32:41.380 --> 00:32:43.680
You can-- some of us
have already been there.

00:32:43.680 --> 00:32:46.350
You can visit it.

00:32:46.350 --> 00:32:49.140
But this was his
household slaves.

00:32:49.140 --> 00:32:51.170
You don't get a sense
of the industry,

00:32:51.170 --> 00:32:53.910
the cruelty of the
industrial slavery

00:32:53.910 --> 00:32:56.550
by looking at these quarters.

00:32:56.550 --> 00:33:00.420
It was what was
going on in Antigua,

00:33:00.420 --> 00:33:04.350
which was continuing to
support his family, that

00:33:04.350 --> 00:33:08.430
was really, really brutal.

00:33:08.430 --> 00:33:10.380
He fled to England
on the outbreak

00:33:10.380 --> 00:33:14.130
of the American Revolution,
the Battle of Lexington.

00:33:14.130 --> 00:33:15.600
Left his family in Medford.

00:33:15.600 --> 00:33:19.710
He ran immediately to Halifax.

00:33:19.710 --> 00:33:23.780
And when I introduce
the students coming in,

00:33:23.780 --> 00:33:26.340
I show them the portrait
we've just seen.

00:33:26.340 --> 00:33:33.920
I say, you know, brutal
slave owner, trader, coward.

00:33:33.920 --> 00:33:36.620
Other than that, a perfect
role model for you.

00:33:36.620 --> 00:33:38.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:40.940 --> 00:33:44.720
Well, in 1936, Abbott
Lawrence Lowell,

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:48.410
who was an anglophile
of the first order,

00:33:48.410 --> 00:33:52.340
decided that Oxford colleges
all had coats of arms,

00:33:52.340 --> 00:33:55.160
so therefore residence
houses and schools at Harvard

00:33:55.160 --> 00:33:58.280
all ought to have
coats of arms, too.

00:33:58.280 --> 00:34:00.410
And so, for the
[INAUDIBLE] he decreed

00:34:00.410 --> 00:34:02.510
coats of arms for everybody.

00:34:02.510 --> 00:34:05.750
And that included
Radcliffe, but it also

00:34:05.750 --> 00:34:07.220
included the law school.

00:34:07.220 --> 00:34:09.500
And the genius who was
assigned the law school

00:34:09.500 --> 00:34:12.679
decided that the
right coat of arms

00:34:12.679 --> 00:34:17.420
should be Isaac
Royall's coat of arms.

00:34:17.420 --> 00:34:20.150
So, there is a book
plate of Isaac Royall.

00:34:20.150 --> 00:34:21.290
Isaac Royall of Antigua.

00:34:21.290 --> 00:34:23.300
You see the three wheat sheaves.

00:34:23.300 --> 00:34:26.060
And there is the coat of
arms of Harvard Law School

00:34:26.060 --> 00:34:27.570
until last year.

00:34:27.570 --> 00:34:29.449
They're identical.

00:34:29.449 --> 00:34:33.560
Well, anyway, the students who
had worked on this research

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:37.340
project persuaded other
students to read the book.

00:34:37.340 --> 00:34:41.090
And before anybody
knew it, they were in--

00:34:41.090 --> 00:34:43.639
they had organized
Students for Inclusion.

00:34:43.639 --> 00:34:46.760
Their motto was
Royall must fall.

00:34:46.760 --> 00:34:50.270
And they took over
the major lounge

00:34:50.270 --> 00:34:52.820
at the new Caspersen
Student Center,

00:34:52.820 --> 00:34:55.699
declared it the
Belinda Lounge, which

00:34:55.699 --> 00:34:58.610
is after the slave,
one of Royall's slaves,

00:34:58.610 --> 00:35:01.560
and occupied it.

00:35:01.560 --> 00:35:05.690
So, they were in
absolute seriousness.

00:35:05.690 --> 00:35:11.960
And a committee was formed under
the chairmanship of Bruce Mann.

00:35:11.960 --> 00:35:15.320
And that committee, after
a lot of deliberation,

00:35:15.320 --> 00:35:18.500
decided to recommend to the
president and corporation

00:35:18.500 --> 00:35:21.500
that the shield be revoked.

00:35:21.500 --> 00:35:25.190
Now, that decision came with a--

00:35:25.190 --> 00:35:27.680
what I think's one of
the most eloquent pieces

00:35:27.680 --> 00:35:29.670
of writing I've ever seen.

00:35:29.670 --> 00:35:34.670
And it's by our moderator,
Annette Gordon-Reed.

00:35:34.670 --> 00:35:40.445
And in that, she
warned that you,

00:35:40.445 --> 00:35:42.320
by just eliminating
a symbol, you

00:35:42.320 --> 00:35:45.890
don't eliminate the
truth of the past.

00:35:45.890 --> 00:35:49.280
And also worried that this
would cut the school off

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:51.099
from the debt it
owes to Antigua.

00:35:51.099 --> 00:35:52.640
By the way, this is
what the students

00:35:52.640 --> 00:35:58.670
thought of the Royall
coat of arms, right?

00:35:58.670 --> 00:36:02.360
That's their view of it.

00:36:02.360 --> 00:36:06.050
Well, anyway, here I
am, down on Antigua.

00:36:06.050 --> 00:36:08.440
That's the Betty's Hope.

00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:13.550
You see the great mills for
breaking up the sugarcane.

00:36:13.550 --> 00:36:18.290
I was down there talking
to leaders in the Antiguan

00:36:18.290 --> 00:36:20.750
community, educational
leaders and the head

00:36:20.750 --> 00:36:23.060
of their national government,
and their secretary

00:36:23.060 --> 00:36:24.820
of education.

00:36:24.820 --> 00:36:30.410
And I was talking
about the consciousness

00:36:30.410 --> 00:36:33.530
of the island and its connection
with Harvard Law School.

00:36:33.530 --> 00:36:36.110
First of all, it turns
out that the curriculum

00:36:36.110 --> 00:36:39.710
in the high schools all
mention Isaac Royall

00:36:39.710 --> 00:36:44.640
and mention the slave revolt.
So, every high school student

00:36:44.640 --> 00:36:46.850
learns this story.

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:49.100
And secondly, that
they're absolutely

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:51.710
mindful of the connection
between the island

00:36:51.710 --> 00:36:54.890
and this university.

00:36:54.890 --> 00:36:56.900
At one point when
talking to Michele Henry,

00:36:56.900 --> 00:37:01.130
the president of
the National Museum,

00:37:01.130 --> 00:37:02.960
I really was just overcome.

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:04.760
I mean, they had
showed me some things

00:37:04.760 --> 00:37:08.330
which they just don't normally
show tourists, of course, which

00:37:08.330 --> 00:37:13.490
is the holding pens for the
slaves, that have survived,

00:37:13.490 --> 00:37:17.570
and the dungeons where they
hung slaves by their wrists

00:37:17.570 --> 00:37:20.960
and which are back
in the jungle.

00:37:20.960 --> 00:37:21.800
And I was overcome.

00:37:21.800 --> 00:37:25.430
And I thought, I said,
well, I'm so sorry.

00:37:25.430 --> 00:37:29.990
I'm so sorry that I represent
here and have benefited

00:37:29.990 --> 00:37:34.940
from an institution that
has exploited and enslaved

00:37:34.940 --> 00:37:36.880
people of this island.

00:37:36.880 --> 00:37:38.780
I'm just sorry.

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:43.160
And, you know, she turned to
me, Michele Henry, and she said,

00:37:43.160 --> 00:37:46.040
you know, don't be sorry.

00:37:46.040 --> 00:37:48.320
Don't be sorry.

00:37:48.320 --> 00:37:51.680
We Antiguans are proud
to have had some role

00:37:51.680 --> 00:37:54.350
in the founding of
an institution that

00:37:54.350 --> 00:37:57.260
would graduate Barack Obama.

00:37:57.260 --> 00:38:00.890
Now that is generousness.

00:38:00.890 --> 00:38:01.890
Here you are.

00:38:01.890 --> 00:38:04.510
There's the poster.

00:38:04.510 --> 00:38:07.280
They're selling Obama t-shirts
everywhere on the island.

00:38:07.280 --> 00:38:10.180
Now my point is
just a simple one,

00:38:10.180 --> 00:38:13.520
which is Annette
Gordon-Reed's dissent stands

00:38:13.520 --> 00:38:16.640
for a very important truth.

00:38:16.640 --> 00:38:20.300
You don't just go around
erasing this and that

00:38:20.300 --> 00:38:23.120
and pretend things
didn't happen.

00:38:23.120 --> 00:38:26.390
You know, there are pros
and cons about the shield

00:38:26.390 --> 00:38:29.180
controversy, but one thing--

00:38:29.180 --> 00:38:32.420
we must not forget that
Harvard Law School is linked

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:35.180
with slavery, that Harvard
Law School owes great debt

00:38:35.180 --> 00:38:36.690
to the enslaved
people of Antigua,

00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:39.740
and that it's part of
this great university

00:38:39.740 --> 00:38:44.930
that it is so great that it can
recognize in itself the truth.

00:38:44.930 --> 00:38:46.160
Veritas.

00:38:46.160 --> 00:38:47.030
Thank you very much.

00:38:47.030 --> 00:38:50.481
[APPLAUSE]

00:38:56.900 --> 00:38:59.750
- So, thank you so much
for the invitation.

00:38:59.750 --> 00:39:02.470
I'm very honored and it's
a pleasure to be here.

00:39:02.470 --> 00:39:05.080
Thanks the Radcliffe, and
thanks, President Faust,

00:39:05.080 --> 00:39:05.930
for the invitation.

00:39:05.930 --> 00:39:10.300
I want to tell you that this
talk is related to Harvard

00:39:10.300 --> 00:39:11.950
but may not be
related to Harvard.

00:39:11.950 --> 00:39:15.820
And I'd like to see how we all
come to terms with the fact

00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:18.880
that I'm not a historian.

00:39:18.880 --> 00:39:21.790
I have to come to terms with
that, you know, somehow.

00:39:21.790 --> 00:39:23.800
But there will be
lots of images.

00:39:23.800 --> 00:39:25.150
I will not describe them.

00:39:25.150 --> 00:39:27.745
So, there's a lecture or kind
of a concept in the images,

00:39:27.745 --> 00:39:29.620
and there's a concept
in the words that I do.

00:39:29.620 --> 00:39:31.244
And I would like to
invite you to think

00:39:31.244 --> 00:39:33.520
about your own memories
when you think,

00:39:33.520 --> 00:39:36.030
and when you look at this work.

00:39:36.030 --> 00:39:38.080
This originated when I
was a student at Harvard,

00:39:38.080 --> 00:39:40.267
kind of the notion of
architecture and memory.

00:39:40.267 --> 00:39:42.100
I was very interested
in that as a research,

00:39:42.100 --> 00:39:43.360
my own personal research.

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:45.340
And that kind of continued.

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:48.650
So, as an architect
and a teacher,

00:39:48.650 --> 00:39:51.430
I've been investigating through
design and design pedagogy

00:39:51.430 --> 00:39:53.650
the relations between
space and memory,

00:39:53.650 --> 00:39:56.020
between architecture and memory.

00:39:56.020 --> 00:39:59.620
I'm interested in the notion
that memory is an action.

00:39:59.620 --> 00:40:00.760
Memory is not an object.

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:02.740
Memory is a verb, not a noun.

00:40:02.740 --> 00:40:05.980
As an action, to remember is
to be present, is to say here

00:40:05.980 --> 00:40:06.910
we are.

00:40:06.910 --> 00:40:10.210
To be present in our complex
present as academics,

00:40:10.210 --> 00:40:14.230
as architects, as
historians, as intellectuals,

00:40:14.230 --> 00:40:17.080
as public intellectuals,
demands a louder and fearless

00:40:17.080 --> 00:40:21.550
truth-speaking and
truth-seeking about our past

00:40:21.550 --> 00:40:24.520
and also about ongoing
plights against humanity,

00:40:24.520 --> 00:40:28.300
such as human trafficking,
genocides, present-day slavery,

00:40:28.300 --> 00:40:30.220
and incarceration, as well.

00:40:30.220 --> 00:40:32.370
So, few words have
been so ubiquitous

00:40:32.370 --> 00:40:35.590
in contemporary culture
as the word memory,

00:40:35.590 --> 00:40:38.770
impacting historiography,
psychoanalysis, visual arts,

00:40:38.770 --> 00:40:43.400
performing arts, poetry, media,
landscapes, architecture,

00:40:43.400 --> 00:40:44.650
public space.

00:40:44.650 --> 00:40:46.600
So, as a result,
architects and artists

00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:48.850
find themselves playing
an important role

00:40:48.850 --> 00:40:51.490
in what we could call public
discourses about history

00:40:51.490 --> 00:40:53.950
and memory.

00:40:53.950 --> 00:40:56.620
Architecture is inherently
a practical and public art.

00:40:56.620 --> 00:40:58.930
It is a practical art
insofar the purpose

00:40:58.930 --> 00:41:02.085
is the driving force, why a
work is called into being.

00:41:02.085 --> 00:41:02.710
[PHONE RINGING]

00:41:02.710 --> 00:41:03.611
I hope it's not mine.

00:41:03.611 --> 00:41:05.495
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:07.080 --> 00:41:07.830
No, it's not mine.

00:41:07.830 --> 00:41:09.270
OK, thank you.

00:41:09.270 --> 00:41:10.680
So, let me recap.

00:41:10.680 --> 00:41:14.130
So, it's a practical
art insofar that purpose

00:41:14.130 --> 00:41:17.010
is the driving force, why a
work is called into being.

00:41:17.010 --> 00:41:19.830
It is a public art in that
the presence of the work

00:41:19.830 --> 00:41:21.780
constructs the space
for public appearance,

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:25.110
in the terms that Hannah
Ardendt described it,

00:41:25.110 --> 00:41:27.330
the space for public appearance.

00:41:27.330 --> 00:41:29.880
So, historically, the
architectural [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:29.880 --> 00:41:32.730
to create a theater for
action and of memory.

00:41:32.730 --> 00:41:36.630
And we can think that landscapes
and buildings, while framing--

00:41:36.630 --> 00:41:39.120
becoming catalysts for
the process of memory,

00:41:39.120 --> 00:41:41.220
serve to frame human experience.

00:41:41.220 --> 00:41:44.910
It is in the face of
catastrophes, historic traumas,

00:41:44.910 --> 00:41:49.060
and human injustices that the
architects and public artists

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:53.070
public roles become increasingly
complex, problematic,

00:41:53.070 --> 00:41:55.050
and, we only hope, necessary.

00:41:55.050 --> 00:41:56.160
We only hope.

00:41:56.160 --> 00:41:58.249
So, how do we position
ourselves when

00:41:58.249 --> 00:41:59.790
working with these
kinds of projects,

00:41:59.790 --> 00:42:04.200
both as teachers, as
architects, as students?

00:42:04.200 --> 00:42:04.950
Think of this.

00:42:04.950 --> 00:42:07.730
The word memorial--
it's historic role

00:42:07.730 --> 00:42:09.400
is to preserve a
memory of the past

00:42:09.400 --> 00:42:12.494
and provide conditions for
new responses in the present.

00:42:12.494 --> 00:42:14.160
This is one of the
maps that my students

00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:16.280
do dealing with
Rhode Island slavery.

00:42:19.900 --> 00:42:21.550
So, think about this point.

00:42:21.550 --> 00:42:25.060
When we say, this is the
public space of the city,

00:42:25.060 --> 00:42:27.910
we usually mean unofficial
monumental space, which,

00:42:27.910 --> 00:42:29.470
using Walter
Benjamin's words, is

00:42:29.470 --> 00:42:32.950
reserved for the celebration
of the history of the victors.

00:42:32.950 --> 00:42:35.284
Memorials and historic
landmarks usually

00:42:35.284 --> 00:42:36.700
celebrate that
memory of those who

00:42:36.700 --> 00:42:40.180
have succeeded at the expense
of the forgotten memory of those

00:42:40.180 --> 00:42:41.580
who have not.

00:42:41.580 --> 00:42:45.790
It forgets the nameless
and the vanquished.

00:42:45.790 --> 00:42:49.610
According to Hannah
Arendt, political equality

00:42:49.610 --> 00:42:50.720
means visibility.

00:42:50.720 --> 00:42:53.600
Conversely, political
inequality and invisibility

00:42:53.600 --> 00:42:55.019
go hand in hand.

00:42:55.019 --> 00:42:57.560
So when we think of institutions
of slavery and its legacies,

00:42:57.560 --> 00:42:59.900
we should look at them
through the lenses of special

00:42:59.900 --> 00:43:03.470
practices-- segregation,
migration, invisibility,

00:43:03.470 --> 00:43:04.370
you know, feels--

00:43:04.370 --> 00:43:06.200
you can think all
of the words that we

00:43:06.200 --> 00:43:10.806
have used are related to
forms of spatial practice.

00:43:10.806 --> 00:43:11.930
But let's think about this.

00:43:11.930 --> 00:43:14.060
Democracy, as Claude
Lefort tells us,

00:43:14.060 --> 00:43:15.980
is based on uncertainty
and legitimized

00:43:15.980 --> 00:43:19.310
by the declaration of rights,
that is, the right to declare.

00:43:19.310 --> 00:43:22.670
Democratic public spaces based
on contestation, on debate,

00:43:22.670 --> 00:43:24.560
on the appearance of others--

00:43:24.560 --> 00:43:27.740
those others, who as an
enigma of a face that resists

00:43:27.740 --> 00:43:31.160
possession, cannot be fully
known and can never be reduced

00:43:31.160 --> 00:43:35.390
to content, as Emmanuel Levinas
philosopher would have said.

00:43:35.390 --> 00:43:37.970
So, I think to a large extent,
the success of democracy

00:43:37.970 --> 00:43:40.440
and of public space can be
measured in its capacity

00:43:40.440 --> 00:43:43.610
to encourage and assist in
the process of disruption

00:43:43.610 --> 00:43:45.584
of that history of the victors.

00:43:45.584 --> 00:43:46.250
We can see this.

00:43:46.250 --> 00:43:49.882
Hopefully we'll do something.

00:43:49.882 --> 00:43:52.340
But I'm interested in thinking
about these kinds of notions

00:43:52.340 --> 00:43:54.590
of public space in relation
to campuses, in relation

00:43:54.590 --> 00:43:57.230
to speech.

00:43:57.230 --> 00:43:59.930
The National Museum
just opened in DC

00:43:59.930 --> 00:44:02.030
means much more than a building.

00:44:02.030 --> 00:44:05.780
Our project in Nantes is more
than a riverfront landscape.

00:44:05.780 --> 00:44:08.040
There are significant
reinscriptions,

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:11.210
you know, of history and
memory in public life.

00:44:11.210 --> 00:44:15.710
These projects are witnesses
to our actions in the present.

00:44:15.710 --> 00:44:18.290
Our actions in the present.

00:44:18.290 --> 00:44:20.750
So, philosophers
like Giorgio Agamben

00:44:20.750 --> 00:44:23.450
have theorized the precision
of the witness in--

00:44:23.450 --> 00:44:26.450
as the basis of an ethical
political relation insofar

00:44:26.450 --> 00:44:29.120
as the witness answers to
the suffering of others

00:44:29.120 --> 00:44:31.087
without usurping the
place of the other.

00:44:31.087 --> 00:44:33.670
That these were the history that
we were talking about before.

00:44:33.670 --> 00:44:37.100
Again, the witness answers
to the suffering of others

00:44:37.100 --> 00:44:39.860
without usurping the
place of the other.

00:44:39.860 --> 00:44:42.080
So, there's a limit
to representation,

00:44:42.080 --> 00:44:44.740
both in writing and
history and in speaking.

00:44:44.740 --> 00:44:49.190
So, witnessing is a way
of seeing and listening

00:44:49.190 --> 00:44:51.890
that requires an acceptance
of vulnerability.

00:44:51.890 --> 00:44:54.920
It requires a renunciation
of the will to mastery.

00:44:54.920 --> 00:44:57.530
For us, trauma--
theories, [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:57.530 --> 00:45:00.710
argues, to bear witness
to the truth of suffering

00:45:00.710 --> 00:45:03.470
of a traumatic event is to
bear witness to that event's

00:45:03.470 --> 00:45:05.660
incomprehensibility.

00:45:05.660 --> 00:45:08.450
This poses problems for
forms of representation,

00:45:08.450 --> 00:45:11.630
teaching, writing, and creating
that attempts to respond

00:45:11.630 --> 00:45:13.460
to the suffering of others.

00:45:13.460 --> 00:45:16.370
Perhaps we can only
breathe your name.

00:45:16.370 --> 00:45:17.692
Breathe your name.

00:45:21.170 --> 00:45:25.400
So, aesthetics should be
at the service of ethics.

00:45:25.400 --> 00:45:27.800
This is the attitude that I
try to bring to my teaching,

00:45:27.800 --> 00:45:30.460
to my projects, and to our
collaborative work with artist

00:45:30.460 --> 00:45:34.970
and professor here at GSD, and
involves an approach of art,

00:45:34.970 --> 00:45:36.970
architecture and
landscape as mediums

00:45:36.970 --> 00:45:40.670
that are capable of shedding
limited set of truth and values

00:45:40.670 --> 00:45:44.210
in a space that is located
between question, publics,

00:45:44.210 --> 00:45:45.590
and practices.

00:45:45.590 --> 00:45:48.850
Questions, publics,
and practices.

00:45:48.850 --> 00:45:51.366
So, when we dealt with
slavery in Rhode Island,

00:45:51.366 --> 00:45:52.990
the history of slavery
in Rhode Island,

00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:55.690
with a series of design
studios that are geared,

00:45:55.690 --> 00:45:58.930
as a pedagogical approach,
geared to create conditions

00:45:58.930 --> 00:46:01.360
for students to encounter
stories that they cannot

00:46:01.360 --> 00:46:01.990
fathom.

00:46:01.990 --> 00:46:04.600
And I want to think Jim Campbell
for all his fantastic work

00:46:04.600 --> 00:46:08.560
and his help in setting
up these discussions.

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:10.870
But these are an attempt
to construct and understand

00:46:10.870 --> 00:46:15.250
history in our present and
think of a field of [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:15.250 --> 00:46:17.080
called cultural sustainability.

00:46:17.080 --> 00:46:20.020
Think about how we deal
with present conditions.

00:46:20.020 --> 00:46:21.761
So, students worked
with mapping,

00:46:21.761 --> 00:46:23.510
students worked with
[? coast, ?] students

00:46:23.510 --> 00:46:26.530
did memory boxes,
worked on texts,

00:46:26.530 --> 00:46:29.180
created images like this one.

00:46:29.180 --> 00:46:32.270
This is Linden Place, the DeWolf
family mansion in Bristol,

00:46:32.270 --> 00:46:35.430
Rhode Island and a montage
of Carl Walker's work.

00:46:35.430 --> 00:46:38.350
But let's remember,
as Jim Campbell also

00:46:38.350 --> 00:46:41.800
mentioned many times, 55% of
the mill workers in Rhode Island

00:46:41.800 --> 00:46:43.210
by 1830 were children.

00:46:43.210 --> 00:46:44.890
So, we have to think about that.

00:46:44.890 --> 00:46:46.390
So, how do we think
about projects

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:48.400
dealing with the coast
of Rhode Island for today

00:46:48.400 --> 00:46:49.700
and for tomorrow?

00:46:49.700 --> 00:46:51.080
This is one of the concepts.

00:46:51.080 --> 00:46:52.090
These are exercises.

00:46:52.090 --> 00:46:54.310
I'll just go very
quickly on this.

00:46:54.310 --> 00:46:56.020
But the point that
I'm trying to make

00:46:56.020 --> 00:46:59.080
is that students can
become cultural activists.

00:46:59.080 --> 00:47:02.510
And interdisciplinary work
is what matters in my mind.

00:47:02.510 --> 00:47:06.460
So, let me go quickly
to a couple of minutes

00:47:06.460 --> 00:47:10.770
on the project for the Memorial
to the Abolition in Nantes

00:47:10.770 --> 00:47:13.870
that we designed
with [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:13.870 --> 00:47:17.860
And let's remind us that,
basically, today, slavery still

00:47:17.860 --> 00:47:21.340
exists and does so globally,
despite the fact that it's now

00:47:21.340 --> 00:47:23.080
globally illegal.

00:47:23.080 --> 00:47:26.440
And it's a question that
we have to ask ourselves.

00:47:26.440 --> 00:47:29.660
And this question
needs a reinforcement

00:47:29.660 --> 00:47:31.660
in the consciousness and
emotional comprehension

00:47:31.660 --> 00:47:36.100
of all of us and new
generations, as well.

00:47:36.100 --> 00:47:39.670
So [INAUDIBLE],
mayor, prime minister,

00:47:39.670 --> 00:47:44.960
and our kind of direct sponsor,
let's say, of this project

00:47:44.960 --> 00:47:48.010
wrote, "By building the memorial
on the banks of the Loire

00:47:48.010 --> 00:47:50.890
in the heart of a city, at
the point from which the slave

00:47:50.890 --> 00:47:53.860
trading [INAUDIBLE]
departed, we recalled

00:47:53.860 --> 00:47:56.680
that the fact that the struggle
for freedom and dignity

00:47:56.680 --> 00:48:00.100
for all human beings is a
fundamental cause inextricably

00:48:00.100 --> 00:48:02.900
linked to our vision of society.

00:48:02.900 --> 00:48:05.050
The memorial hopes
to become a living

00:48:05.050 --> 00:48:08.364
place for collective commitment
to the memory of the past

00:48:08.364 --> 00:48:10.780
and to continue our struggle
for recognition and promotion

00:48:10.780 --> 00:48:11.800
of human rights."

00:48:11.800 --> 00:48:15.130
This is a key point in
public space, in public life,

00:48:15.130 --> 00:48:16.400
in public speech.

00:48:16.400 --> 00:48:19.550
How do we deal with our present?

00:48:19.550 --> 00:48:21.170
So, the city has
created this kind

00:48:21.170 --> 00:48:24.890
of [INAUDIBLE] that connects
the museum to the memorial.

00:48:24.890 --> 00:48:28.580
And you can see kind of an
aerial view of the site.

00:48:28.580 --> 00:48:31.260
And I'll show you, just to
give you a sense of scale,

00:48:31.260 --> 00:48:33.000
this is Radcliffe,
and this is Harvard.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:34.100
Can you see the map?

00:48:34.100 --> 00:48:37.080
Just quickly, this is
Radcliffe Quad, where we are,

00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:40.070
and this is Massachusetts Hall.

00:48:40.070 --> 00:48:42.650
This is the scale
of the memorial,

00:48:42.650 --> 00:48:44.150
just to give you
a sense of scale.

00:48:44.150 --> 00:48:47.360
The relation is basically
the same distance, twice,

00:48:47.360 --> 00:48:49.940
because you walk it
up above and below.

00:48:49.940 --> 00:48:52.850
So, the concept here
is that the city itself

00:48:52.850 --> 00:48:55.250
has turned its architecture
and official public space

00:48:55.250 --> 00:48:58.590
into a grand reinscription,
and I would say disruptive

00:48:58.590 --> 00:49:00.490
in narrative intervention.

00:49:00.490 --> 00:49:03.590
They not only accepted this,
but embraced this concept,

00:49:03.590 --> 00:49:05.990
that this space, beyond
its symbolic purpose,

00:49:05.990 --> 00:49:07.580
it's useful to
commemorate the event

00:49:07.580 --> 00:49:09.680
and to think about the present.

00:49:09.680 --> 00:49:11.150
So, we excavated.

00:49:11.150 --> 00:49:13.122
We have found an
underground space.

00:49:13.122 --> 00:49:14.830
And we transformed
that underground space

00:49:14.830 --> 00:49:17.000
on the coast of a river,
and we transform it

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:20.150
into a place for people to
come and read and to think.

00:49:20.150 --> 00:49:25.060
So, the project celebrates
the great rupture of abolition

00:49:25.060 --> 00:49:27.170
with the thrust of a
great slanted plate, which

00:49:27.170 --> 00:49:29.780
emerges through the
city and cuts the soil.

00:49:29.780 --> 00:49:37.230
About five centuries of struggle
are inscribed in this glass.

00:49:37.230 --> 00:49:41.300
We also inscribed, kind of as
a form of an urban archive,

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:43.820
the names of 2000
expeditions from Nantes,

00:49:43.820 --> 00:49:45.020
that departed from Nantes.

00:49:45.020 --> 00:49:47.184
And you see people looking
at them and walking,

00:49:47.184 --> 00:49:48.350
and you see beautiful names.

00:49:48.350 --> 00:49:49.860
You can see La Therese.

00:49:49.860 --> 00:49:51.110
There's a ship called L'Amour.

00:49:51.110 --> 00:49:52.960
Can you believe that?

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:55.220
The Three Marys.

00:49:55.220 --> 00:49:56.690
Another Love, you know.

00:49:56.690 --> 00:49:59.030
And they are all
navires negriers.

00:49:59.030 --> 00:50:03.560
So, I want to invite you
to think about the notion

00:50:03.560 --> 00:50:05.120
that when we walk, we think.

00:50:05.120 --> 00:50:06.740
When we walk, we evoke.

00:50:06.740 --> 00:50:08.420
And this is part of what we do.

00:50:08.420 --> 00:50:10.760
The stones themselves matter.

00:50:10.760 --> 00:50:15.680
And the place itself only can be
done if we really pay not only

00:50:15.680 --> 00:50:18.290
respect and homage to the
people who suffered this story,

00:50:18.290 --> 00:50:20.123
but actually we pay
homage to the people who

00:50:20.123 --> 00:50:22.790
made this possible, the
builders, the people who

00:50:22.790 --> 00:50:25.970
put their hands and their
knowledge into making

00:50:25.970 --> 00:50:27.440
our buildings possible.

00:50:27.440 --> 00:50:28.850
This is, to me,
what matters when

00:50:28.850 --> 00:50:31.620
we do buildings, when we do
architecture anywhere we do it.

00:50:31.620 --> 00:50:33.260
How do we engage with others?

00:50:33.260 --> 00:50:34.630
And that's an ethical dimension.

00:50:34.630 --> 00:50:39.080
So, cutting the concrete, going
underground and transforming

00:50:39.080 --> 00:50:41.840
this, which is kind of
flooding with the water

00:50:41.840 --> 00:50:44.540
daily, into a place
that can be inhabited,

00:50:44.540 --> 00:50:47.230
creating a dam underground,
a complex structure.

00:50:47.230 --> 00:50:49.530
This space is about 150
meters below ground.

00:50:49.530 --> 00:50:51.950
That's a football field
and a half length.

00:50:51.950 --> 00:50:54.360
You know, and you see how
it goes and how it moves,

00:50:54.360 --> 00:50:54.860
and you're--

00:50:54.860 --> 00:50:57.260
I'm just getting
close to the finish.

00:50:57.260 --> 00:50:59.750
So, you see how this
glass transforms

00:50:59.750 --> 00:51:00.760
the ground of a city.

00:51:00.760 --> 00:51:03.660
And very significant moments
of opening of the memorial.

00:51:03.660 --> 00:51:06.290
And I want to pay significant
homage to Madame [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:06.290 --> 00:51:09.590
who's here and will
speak later, for her work

00:51:09.590 --> 00:51:12.106
not only to support the
memorial and her speech

00:51:12.106 --> 00:51:13.730
at the opening of
the memorial, but her

00:51:13.730 --> 00:51:16.550
work specifically
to bring justice,

00:51:16.550 --> 00:51:20.270
to bring the law that is under
your name to the public eye

00:51:20.270 --> 00:51:22.040
in France and in the world.

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:23.791
So, that law is inscribed
in the memorial,

00:51:23.791 --> 00:51:25.498
or a good portion of
the law is inscribed

00:51:25.498 --> 00:51:28.490
in the memorial in a space that
looks at the Palace of Justice.

00:51:28.490 --> 00:51:29.750
So, we have people visiting.

00:51:29.750 --> 00:51:30.740
We have people reading.

00:51:30.740 --> 00:51:33.500
We have people
inhabiting a space that

00:51:33.500 --> 00:51:36.100
relates to the water,
a water that perhaps

00:51:36.100 --> 00:51:39.260
is the only witness, somehow,
to the story, a water that

00:51:39.260 --> 00:51:42.170
filters, a water that comes down
through the glass, a water that

00:51:42.170 --> 00:51:45.240
marks words, words like freedom.

00:51:45.240 --> 00:51:46.340
And you see people coming.

00:51:46.340 --> 00:51:49.610
You see groups and schools
reading and writing

00:51:49.610 --> 00:51:51.290
and thinking and discussing.

00:51:51.290 --> 00:51:53.660
And yes, these are my two kids.

00:51:53.660 --> 00:51:56.426
And, basically-- and we have
Martin Luther King that is also

00:51:56.426 --> 00:51:58.550
inscribed there, and you
see emotion that happened,

00:51:58.550 --> 00:52:01.520
and you see also revolt. A
moment two years ago when

00:52:01.520 --> 00:52:03.300
Angela Davis was
visiting the memorial

00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:06.530
as a kind of a
day of remembrance

00:52:06.530 --> 00:52:08.270
of the abolition of slavery.

00:52:08.270 --> 00:52:12.980
So, I'm going to finish with
just one word, which is this--

00:52:12.980 --> 00:52:15.380
When we did this project,
we didn't know the outcome.

00:52:15.380 --> 00:52:17.850
I mean, we knew
that space matters.

00:52:17.850 --> 00:52:20.516
And space and memory
are totally connected.

00:52:20.516 --> 00:52:21.890
So, when you look
at the memorial

00:52:21.890 --> 00:52:24.890
from the Palace of Justice,
you see a line, horizontal line

00:52:24.890 --> 00:52:26.270
on the ground of the city.

00:52:26.270 --> 00:52:28.670
But when you go to the
memorial, you see justice.

00:52:28.670 --> 00:52:31.790
You imagine justice, or perhaps
justice that needs to be done.

00:52:31.790 --> 00:52:34.490
There's no inscription that
says, think about justice.

00:52:34.490 --> 00:52:36.830
But you do that, because we
can kind of construct it,

00:52:36.830 --> 00:52:38.350
that relation, that dialogue.

00:52:38.350 --> 00:52:40.400
And that dialogue
happens in space.

00:52:40.400 --> 00:52:42.950
And that dialogue happens
when I saw this woman visibly

00:52:42.950 --> 00:52:44.497
emotional looking
at the memorial

00:52:44.497 --> 00:52:45.580
and visiting the memorial.

00:52:45.580 --> 00:52:48.470
And I heard footsteps running.

00:52:48.470 --> 00:52:50.410
And I heard-- and I saw her son.

00:52:50.410 --> 00:52:51.830
And I saw this embrace.

00:52:51.830 --> 00:52:55.990
And I want to close by saying,
using Levinas's citation

00:52:55.990 --> 00:53:00.350
of Dostoyevsky, who
also was interestingly

00:53:00.350 --> 00:53:03.050
connected to James Baldwin's
understanding of memory,

00:53:03.050 --> 00:53:05.560
as far as I read.

00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:09.580
So, Dostoevsky says all of us
are responsible of everything,

00:53:09.580 --> 00:53:13.877
of everyone before everyone,
and myself more than others.

00:53:13.877 --> 00:53:14.710
Thank you very much.

