00:54:51.690 --> 00:54:54.090
And the mayor was extremely
supportive of that.

00:54:54.090 --> 00:54:54.969
That's one thing.

00:54:54.969 --> 00:54:57.510
Second thing is that there was
a history before the memorial,

00:54:57.510 --> 00:55:00.480
which was the Les Anneaux de
la Memoire, a very significant

00:55:00.480 --> 00:55:04.680
exhibition that happened in 1992
that had about half a million

00:55:04.680 --> 00:55:08.640
people visiting the Chateau
de Nantes, the duc de

00:55:08.640 --> 00:55:12.240
Bretagne, basically to
visit and to understand

00:55:12.240 --> 00:55:13.500
the history of its own city.

00:55:13.500 --> 00:55:14.874
So, it seems to
me that there are

00:55:14.874 --> 00:55:18.210
some aspects of the
story that were extremely

00:55:18.210 --> 00:55:20.300
important in the public eye.

00:55:20.300 --> 00:55:23.490
The people who did not
want this to happen

00:55:23.490 --> 00:55:26.430
came from either
families or more,

00:55:26.430 --> 00:55:29.100
I would say, right-wing
kind of areas

00:55:29.100 --> 00:55:35.700
of the people in the city,
but once the memorial opened,

00:55:35.700 --> 00:55:37.080
it was embraced.

00:55:37.080 --> 00:55:39.660
Once the memorial opened, it
was embraced by the people

00:55:39.660 --> 00:55:40.260
and visited.

00:55:40.260 --> 00:55:43.080
And everybody brings family
to visit the memorial,

00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:46.770
and they see this as a unique
project, both in the city

00:55:46.770 --> 00:55:48.370
and in France.

00:55:48.370 --> 00:55:50.340
And I think-- I'm
personally very

00:55:50.340 --> 00:55:54.180
moved to have been simply
be able to visualize this,

00:55:54.180 --> 00:55:58.110
to visualize this project and to
inhabit that space that nobody

00:55:58.110 --> 00:56:00.852
has ever seen
before we opened it.

00:56:00.852 --> 00:56:03.060
It is a space that was
excavated that no one has ever

00:56:03.060 --> 00:56:06.660
seen before, because it was just
simply residue of construction

00:56:06.660 --> 00:56:09.060
of the ports.

00:56:09.060 --> 00:56:11.760
- Dan, for the
people in Antigua,

00:56:11.760 --> 00:56:16.320
have you heard any response
to them about the shield?

00:56:16.320 --> 00:56:19.200
Or do you-- can
you sort of predict

00:56:19.200 --> 00:56:23.480
what they might say about it?

00:56:23.480 --> 00:56:28.490
- Well, they are
aware of the decision.

00:56:28.490 --> 00:56:34.160
And they have copy of the
opinion and of your dissent.

00:56:34.160 --> 00:56:38.150
So, this is-- these
are people who

00:56:38.150 --> 00:56:41.990
are really keeping track here.

00:56:41.990 --> 00:56:46.070
There's no question that they're
not interested in reparation

00:56:46.070 --> 00:56:47.250
or anything like that.

00:56:47.250 --> 00:56:49.010
That's not what interests them.

00:56:49.010 --> 00:56:52.340
What interests them
is some recognition

00:56:52.340 --> 00:56:55.790
by this great
university that they--

00:56:55.790 --> 00:57:00.060
that we owe them a
debt, an historic debt.

00:57:00.060 --> 00:57:02.870
And there are many possible
ways-- they don't have enough--

00:57:02.870 --> 00:57:04.245
when I was down
there, there were

00:57:04.245 --> 00:57:07.710
lines to use laptop
computers in the library.

00:57:07.710 --> 00:57:09.590
There are not enough computers.

00:57:09.590 --> 00:57:11.570
There's also not
enough fresh water.

00:57:11.570 --> 00:57:14.870
And they're having problems
with their justice system.

00:57:14.870 --> 00:57:18.350
So, I mean, there are so many
things we could do to help.

00:57:18.350 --> 00:57:22.210
- I think I should
probably say what

00:57:22.210 --> 00:57:26.885
happened with the dissent,
what my rationale was.

00:57:29.860 --> 00:57:33.200
You know, this whole question--

00:57:33.200 --> 00:57:35.030
a lot of it comes
from, I mean, I

00:57:35.030 --> 00:57:38.510
think the Royall must
fall was influenced

00:57:38.510 --> 00:57:41.780
by the movement at Oxford
about Oriel College,

00:57:41.780 --> 00:57:43.630
Rhodes must fall.

00:57:43.630 --> 00:57:47.540
There was a statue of Cecil
Rhodes on top of Oriel College,

00:57:47.540 --> 00:57:49.580
that I've been into
a number of times

00:57:49.580 --> 00:57:50.960
and never knew he was up there.

00:57:50.960 --> 00:57:53.180
He was up pretty high.

00:57:53.180 --> 00:57:56.000
And the thinking was
that this was an affront.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:57:59.120
And there was a student
movement on those lines.

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:01.880
On our committee, we were
talking about the best way

00:58:01.880 --> 00:58:03.030
to proceed.

00:58:03.030 --> 00:58:05.900
And it's not that
I think that it

00:58:05.900 --> 00:58:07.940
would be a matter
of erasing history

00:58:07.940 --> 00:58:11.420
just by moving the shield.

00:58:11.420 --> 00:58:13.100
The idea I had was that--

00:58:13.100 --> 00:58:15.380
and I talked in the dissent
about the difference

00:58:15.380 --> 00:58:18.260
between a representation
of a person who

00:58:18.260 --> 00:58:22.280
can't be reconstituted, someone
like Cecil Rhodes or John

00:58:22.280 --> 00:58:25.790
Calhoun, a flag like
the Confederate flag

00:58:25.790 --> 00:58:30.890
that has a history and a past
and is so imbued with a spirit

00:58:30.890 --> 00:58:34.790
that you can't, to
my mind, do away

00:58:34.790 --> 00:58:37.400
with what that meant in
terms of the Confederacy

00:58:37.400 --> 00:58:39.770
or what it meant in
its modern incarnation

00:58:39.770 --> 00:58:43.490
with people taking it and using
it to oppose civil rights,

00:58:43.490 --> 00:58:46.160
and when it's hauled out
and why it's hauled out.

00:58:46.160 --> 00:58:47.460
That's-- it's not like that.

00:58:47.460 --> 00:58:50.870
Three bushels of
wheat are symbols.

00:58:50.870 --> 00:58:53.480
When my husband and I
were here as students,

00:58:53.480 --> 00:58:54.800
we had no idea what it meant.

00:58:54.800 --> 00:58:57.170
I thought, well, OK,
sheaves of wheat.

00:58:57.170 --> 00:59:00.440
Fertility, knowledge,
what is this?

00:59:00.440 --> 00:59:01.940
We really didn't know.

00:59:01.940 --> 00:59:08.180
And we had wheat pennies, but
wheat is a symbol of abundance

00:59:08.180 --> 00:59:08.850
and so forth.

00:59:08.850 --> 00:59:11.210
So, we sort of think, abundance
of wisdom or something--

00:59:11.210 --> 00:59:12.020
you give it a name.

00:59:12.020 --> 00:59:13.970
So, it could mean anything.

00:59:13.970 --> 00:59:16.970
And it struck me that
since we were having

00:59:16.970 --> 00:59:23.190
our centennial, what we could
do would be to have a ceremony

00:59:23.190 --> 00:59:27.930
and reconstitute the law
school and the sheaves of wheat

00:59:27.930 --> 00:59:31.200
to be in honor of
the people whose

00:59:31.200 --> 00:59:37.040
labor gave Isaac Royall the
money to build the law school.

00:59:37.040 --> 00:59:42.140
It's the power of law, what
we do is transformative.

00:59:42.140 --> 00:59:43.930
We could make the
symbol about whatever

00:59:43.930 --> 00:59:45.670
we want it to be about.

00:59:45.670 --> 00:59:49.810
And my fear-- and to
have that powerful symbol

00:59:49.810 --> 00:59:53.890
there go across the world every
time Harvard Law School went

00:59:53.890 --> 00:59:56.890
anywhere, I thought
would be powerful,

00:59:56.890 --> 01:00:01.240
that the people on the Royall
plantation would be remembered.

01:00:01.240 --> 01:00:03.700
And they would be remembered
in a way that would be living

01:00:03.700 --> 01:00:04.930
and would go forward.

01:00:04.930 --> 01:00:09.370
It's nice to have a
display in the law

01:00:09.370 --> 01:00:10.960
school and the
special collections

01:00:10.960 --> 01:00:14.290
and talk about it amongst
ourselves when students come.

01:00:14.290 --> 01:00:16.030
But it would be
different to have

01:00:16.030 --> 01:00:17.860
Harvard Law School linked--

01:00:17.860 --> 01:00:22.450
Harvard Law School that under,
I think, the modern ages

01:00:22.450 --> 01:00:26.647
of Harvard Law School when the
shield was actually used more--

01:00:26.647 --> 01:00:28.105
Harvard has a
tradition, law school

01:00:28.105 --> 01:00:30.310
has a tradition
of public service.

01:00:30.310 --> 01:00:32.830
Many people were
involved in civil rights.

01:00:32.830 --> 01:00:35.470
That legacy could be
linked to the old legacy

01:00:35.470 --> 01:00:37.150
to make something new.

01:00:37.150 --> 01:00:39.949
We're not bound by
the past in that way.

01:00:39.949 --> 01:00:40.990
So, that was my thinking.

01:00:40.990 --> 01:00:44.020
It's not from any love or
respect of Isaac Royall,

01:00:44.020 --> 01:00:46.990
but the Royall plantation was
not about Isaac Royall, to me.

01:00:46.990 --> 01:00:49.180
The Royall plantation was
about the enslaved people

01:00:49.180 --> 01:00:50.500
who lived there.

01:00:50.500 --> 01:00:52.630
And that is the story.

01:00:52.630 --> 01:00:54.340
And we could make
the story what we

01:00:54.340 --> 01:00:57.250
wanted it to be rather
than being hostage

01:00:57.250 --> 01:00:58.780
to Isaac Royall and his family.

01:00:58.780 --> 01:01:00.700
So, that was my thinking.

01:01:00.700 --> 01:01:05.290
Ceremony, reconstitute it, we
go forward with a different--

01:01:05.290 --> 01:01:09.100
perhaps add the word, you
know, justice, for justice

01:01:09.100 --> 01:01:12.700
to the shield and make
that association complete.

01:01:12.700 --> 01:01:14.830
So, that's what my thinking was.

01:01:14.830 --> 01:01:18.805
It was not out of
isn't Royall great.

01:01:18.805 --> 01:01:20.080
- Can I just--

01:01:20.080 --> 01:01:21.786
I just wanted to
add a few things.

01:01:21.786 --> 01:01:23.410
I mean, for one, I
think what is really

01:01:23.410 --> 01:01:26.050
important is that
whatever we do,

01:01:26.050 --> 01:01:28.570
that we don't take
the steps that we're

01:01:28.570 --> 01:01:33.880
taking as a kind of an effort
to end the conversation

01:01:33.880 --> 01:01:38.050
or to end our engagement
with this history,

01:01:38.050 --> 01:01:40.240
but really that we
commit ourselves

01:01:40.240 --> 01:01:43.600
to a continued conversation
of this history

01:01:43.600 --> 01:01:45.620
and a continued confrontation
with this history.

01:01:45.620 --> 01:01:48.130
And I think the worst
thing we could do

01:01:48.130 --> 01:01:52.512
is kind of to cleanse our
institutions from this history

01:01:52.512 --> 01:01:54.220
and then to say, oh,
we took care of that

01:01:54.220 --> 01:01:56.220
and now we don't have to
worry about it anymore.

01:01:56.220 --> 01:01:58.780
No, I think we need to
continue to engage with this.

01:01:58.780 --> 01:02:01.144
And then I thought,
maybe the experience

01:02:01.144 --> 01:02:02.560
of the city of
Nantes in some ways

01:02:02.560 --> 01:02:06.760
is actually quite
relevant to our situation

01:02:06.760 --> 01:02:10.810
here because, obviously, Nantes
is not a city that was, itself,

01:02:10.810 --> 01:02:13.210
the site of mass enslavement.

01:02:13.210 --> 01:02:15.160
It is not a city that
was characterized

01:02:15.160 --> 01:02:17.500
by slave plantations.

01:02:17.500 --> 01:02:19.790
And it is a city in
which, presumably,

01:02:19.790 --> 01:02:21.290
though I don't know
that for a fact,

01:02:21.290 --> 01:02:23.290
but in which presumably
many people don't really

01:02:23.290 --> 01:02:26.830
know anymore that it had
this very significant link

01:02:26.830 --> 01:02:30.490
to the slave trade and
to Caribbean slavery.

01:02:30.490 --> 01:02:34.000
And that is, I think, quite
similar to the situation

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:35.980
we're facing here at Harvard.

01:02:35.980 --> 01:02:39.160
And so it would actually be
quite interesting to learn,

01:02:39.160 --> 01:02:41.860
for us to learn from
the Nantes experience

01:02:41.860 --> 01:02:47.090
to see how you can memorialize
this history on the one hand,

01:02:47.090 --> 01:02:51.160
but also how you can encourage
a continued conversation

01:02:51.160 --> 01:02:53.560
on that history and how
you, as Julian mentioned,

01:02:53.560 --> 01:02:56.800
how you can persuade people
who are reluctant to engage

01:02:56.800 --> 01:03:00.010
in this debate to eventually
persuade them to actually,

01:03:00.010 --> 01:03:02.860
to engage these kinds of issues.

01:03:02.860 --> 01:03:04.930
I think there is a
lesson in it for us,

01:03:04.930 --> 01:03:07.030
though I don't know exactly
what that lesson is.

01:03:07.030 --> 01:03:08.860
- Well, one of the things that's
happening at the law school

01:03:08.860 --> 01:03:10.860
now, we're going to be
encouraging people to do,

01:03:10.860 --> 01:03:14.520
that since we have the royal
plantation, not very far, is--

01:03:14.520 --> 01:03:17.800
and Janet Halley is doing this,
encouraging people to visit.

01:03:17.800 --> 01:03:19.390
I've been there.

01:03:19.390 --> 01:03:22.210
And they do a great
interpretation,

01:03:22.210 --> 01:03:26.200
very illuminating interpretation
about slavery in New England

01:03:26.200 --> 01:03:27.730
and the lives of
the people there.

01:03:27.730 --> 01:03:29.290
Maybe have our--
well, obviously,

01:03:29.290 --> 01:03:31.360
have our students go there.

01:03:31.360 --> 01:03:33.070
I would like, as part
of what I thought

01:03:33.070 --> 01:03:36.160
would go on after a perhaps
reconstituted shield

01:03:36.160 --> 01:03:38.170
and re-dedication,
we would be, we

01:03:38.170 --> 01:03:41.470
would have more of a connection
to the people in Antigua.

01:03:41.470 --> 01:03:45.640
Maybe students, some connection
there to keep the thing going

01:03:45.640 --> 01:03:48.490
instead of just letting it go.

01:03:48.490 --> 01:03:51.760
But that-- any kind of
experiences from other places

01:03:51.760 --> 01:03:54.217
should help inform us.

01:03:54.217 --> 01:03:55.300
Here's a question for you.

01:03:55.300 --> 01:03:58.330
Professor Beckert, thank
you for your presentation

01:03:58.330 --> 01:04:01.090
and ongoing commitment to
justice for enslaved Africans'

01:04:01.090 --> 01:04:02.320
descendants.

01:04:02.320 --> 01:04:04.630
You said the solution must
be economic and not just

01:04:04.630 --> 01:04:06.460
rhetorical or symbolic.

01:04:06.460 --> 01:04:10.690
Do you support reparations
to specific organizations

01:04:10.690 --> 01:04:15.130
who build African
self-determination?

01:04:15.130 --> 01:04:17.470
I'm sorry for putting
you on the spot.

01:04:17.470 --> 01:04:20.020
- OK, no, no, no,
that's just fair

01:04:20.020 --> 01:04:22.790
because I ended my talk
exactly on this notion.

01:04:22.790 --> 01:04:24.670
And honestly, that was
very much the subject

01:04:24.670 --> 01:04:27.220
of our conversations
this morning.

01:04:27.220 --> 01:04:32.440
And yes, as I said, I think
it is important to acknowledge

01:04:32.440 --> 01:04:33.220
this history.

01:04:33.220 --> 01:04:36.340
It is important to know
what that history is.

01:04:36.340 --> 01:04:41.170
And we have made some
progress in this process.

01:04:41.170 --> 01:04:44.530
But I think we also need
to very much keep in mind

01:04:44.530 --> 01:04:47.050
what was being said today.

01:04:47.050 --> 01:04:53.410
This is a history that is
about massive violence.

01:04:53.410 --> 01:04:56.170
This is a history of racism.

01:04:56.170 --> 01:05:00.910
And this is also a history
of massive dispossession,

01:05:00.910 --> 01:05:03.750
as was also mentioned
earlier today.

01:05:03.750 --> 01:05:07.870
And all of the violence, the
racism, and the dispossession

01:05:07.870 --> 01:05:08.940
has--

01:05:08.940 --> 01:05:11.890
it's not just of relevance
to understanding the past,

01:05:11.890 --> 01:05:13.390
but it's also very
much of relevance

01:05:13.390 --> 01:05:15.820
to understanding the present.

01:05:15.820 --> 01:05:19.330
And in that way, I think
there is a material

01:05:19.330 --> 01:05:22.560
dimension to this issue.

01:05:22.560 --> 01:05:28.570
And there is a need for
institutions, or perhaps

01:05:28.570 --> 01:05:33.730
nations, who have greatly
benefited from exploitation,

01:05:33.730 --> 01:05:36.880
racism, enslavement, and
dispossession-- there

01:05:36.880 --> 01:05:43.000
is a responsibility to
address these past injustices,

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:46.350
and also address them
in material terms.

01:05:46.350 --> 01:05:50.020
What this exactly looks
like, I can't tell.

01:05:50.020 --> 01:05:54.550
But I think the importance
is to acknowledge this

01:05:54.550 --> 01:05:58.330
and then to have a
conversation among a community,

01:05:58.330 --> 01:06:00.490
for example, a
university community,

01:06:00.490 --> 01:06:05.950
to see what the proper steps
are that should be taken.

01:06:05.950 --> 01:06:08.950
- Julian, and I
thought this myself,

01:06:08.950 --> 01:06:15.800
what would a memorial to
slavery at Harvard look like?

01:06:15.800 --> 01:06:18.010
And how do you
garner your support?

01:06:18.010 --> 01:06:18.631
- And how?

01:06:18.631 --> 01:06:19.130
Sorry?

01:06:19.130 --> 01:06:21.617
- How do you garner
your support?

01:06:21.617 --> 01:06:23.075
The first one,
what-- if you were--

01:06:23.075 --> 01:06:25.400
what would a memorial
at slavery look--

01:06:25.400 --> 01:06:28.520
at Harvard look like?

01:06:28.520 --> 01:06:34.400
- I think it's a question
that I cannot answer,

01:06:34.400 --> 01:06:40.530
because in order to conceive or
think through such an endeavor

01:06:40.530 --> 01:06:43.530
once requires time
to think about it.

01:06:43.530 --> 01:06:47.060
And, to me, it's
not that I'm trying

01:06:47.060 --> 01:06:51.720
to sort of short-change or sort
of shy away from the response,

01:06:51.720 --> 01:06:54.860
is actually that there
may be other ways

01:06:54.860 --> 01:06:56.270
in which one can think of this.

01:06:56.270 --> 01:06:59.930
I am personally more
interested in the word memory

01:06:59.930 --> 01:07:02.450
than in the word memorial
even though we have built it.

01:07:02.450 --> 01:07:06.170
I mean to say that how we
think about memory, relation

01:07:06.170 --> 01:07:08.290
to the past, but
memory is remembering.

01:07:08.290 --> 01:07:12.050
You know, James Baldwin's
unfinished book,

01:07:12.050 --> 01:07:15.010
Remembering This House, the
notion of remembering a house.

01:07:15.010 --> 01:07:17.360
So, then the question
that I ask myself is,

01:07:17.360 --> 01:07:24.480
if I can follow up with that, is
once we think of this history,

01:07:24.480 --> 01:07:28.170
we somehow shed light over
a portion of a history.

01:07:28.170 --> 01:07:29.590
You know, imagine a lamp.

01:07:29.590 --> 01:07:31.950
You don't shed light
over the totality

01:07:31.950 --> 01:07:33.750
of the history of slavery.

01:07:33.750 --> 01:07:36.360
So, some aspects we can see.

01:07:36.360 --> 01:07:38.310
Some aspects we cannot see.

01:07:38.310 --> 01:07:42.450
But what we can see,
we cannot unsee.

01:07:42.450 --> 01:07:44.430
And this is an important
aspect of the question

01:07:44.430 --> 01:07:46.380
of the lamp of memory.

01:07:46.380 --> 01:07:50.190
And the question I ask myself
is once we see something,

01:07:50.190 --> 01:07:54.480
it continues to be with us, so
how do we allow that what we

01:07:54.480 --> 01:07:58.320
see to interrupt our
present, meaning how can

01:07:58.320 --> 01:08:01.120
we hear the voices of
those who are not present?

01:08:01.120 --> 01:08:05.020
How can we see these
faces that we see here?

01:08:05.020 --> 01:08:10.920
But how can we understand that
the retrospective projection

01:08:10.920 --> 01:08:13.560
of meaning is very complex.

01:08:13.560 --> 01:08:15.810
So, for me, one of the biggest
questions I ask myself,

01:08:15.810 --> 01:08:18.720
and perhaps it's a question
for the university, perhaps,

01:08:18.720 --> 01:08:21.479
is how do we deal with
our present conditions?

01:08:21.479 --> 01:08:25.229
How do we invite our students'
interdisciplinary work

01:08:25.229 --> 01:08:28.100
to consider the present?

01:08:28.100 --> 01:08:30.870
Be that mass incarceration,
be that sex trafficking,

01:08:30.870 --> 01:08:33.479
or human trafficking
today, which are

01:08:33.479 --> 01:08:35.765
enormous and quite significant.

01:08:35.765 --> 01:08:37.890
So, if there was a kind of
a memorial I would think

01:08:37.890 --> 01:08:41.279
of more like an institution
that is an ongoing project that

01:08:41.279 --> 01:08:45.750
never finish, never finishes,
because perhaps to repair--

01:08:45.750 --> 01:08:47.470
and I'm just going
to use a Hebrew word.

01:08:47.470 --> 01:08:48.979
Tikkun is to repair.

01:08:48.979 --> 01:08:51.294
Tikkun olam is to
repair the world.

01:08:51.294 --> 01:08:52.710
And perhaps we are
all here trying

01:08:52.710 --> 01:08:56.460
to do our best to
repair what we can.

01:08:56.460 --> 01:09:00.090
And to me, that's something that
I would like to think about,

01:09:00.090 --> 01:09:02.439
perhaps the university
could engage with.

01:09:02.439 --> 01:09:05.580
It's a conversation first.

01:09:05.580 --> 01:09:07.200
- Dan this was one
to you, but I might

01:09:07.200 --> 01:09:09.359
be able to answer
part of this as well.

01:09:09.359 --> 01:09:11.760
To what extent do you
think the legacy of slavery

01:09:11.760 --> 01:09:15.330
at HLS affected curriculum
or sustained the development

01:09:15.330 --> 01:09:18.672
of legal thought at HLS?

01:09:18.672 --> 01:09:19.755
- That's a great question.

01:09:23.535 --> 01:09:28.020
Basically, what happened
before the Civil War

01:09:28.020 --> 01:09:31.859
is question of memory, with
the Confederate leaders

01:09:31.859 --> 01:09:34.470
and the Union leaders
remembering being

01:09:34.470 --> 01:09:35.910
taught very different things.

01:09:38.800 --> 01:09:41.220
The Confederate-- one of
the Confederate leaders

01:09:41.220 --> 01:09:45.029
was held here in Castle Island
and wrote an irate letter

01:09:45.029 --> 01:09:47.160
to his law professor,
Emory Washburn,

01:09:47.160 --> 01:09:51.000
saying that he didn't understand
why Emory isn't supporting him,

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:53.760
because he, after all, was
fighting for the state's rights

01:09:53.760 --> 01:09:57.180
that Emory Washburn taught
him in the classroom

01:09:57.180 --> 01:09:59.060
at Harvard Law School.

01:09:59.060 --> 01:10:03.460
Washburn sent him a book,
by the way, to read.

01:10:03.460 --> 01:10:09.450
But in all seriousness, one of
the things that the Civil War

01:10:09.450 --> 01:10:12.720
episode at Harvard
Law School shows

01:10:12.720 --> 01:10:15.390
is that there was an effort,
a very deliberate effort,

01:10:15.390 --> 01:10:18.090
by Charles Warren, and I know
you're the Charles Warren

01:10:18.090 --> 01:10:20.700
Professor and I'm the Charles
Warren Visiting Professor,

01:10:20.700 --> 01:10:22.800
but the first history
of Harvard Law School

01:10:22.800 --> 01:10:26.280
was a three-volume
history, only one century,

01:10:26.280 --> 01:10:28.230
written by Charles Warren.

01:10:28.230 --> 01:10:31.050
Charles Warren essentially
took the Civil War out

01:10:31.050 --> 01:10:32.760
of the history of the school.

01:10:32.760 --> 01:10:35.760
And he did it very deliberately,
because at that point

01:10:35.760 --> 01:10:38.790
the school was reaching
out to its Southern alumni

01:10:38.790 --> 01:10:41.520
and bringing in the former
Confederate officers who

01:10:41.520 --> 01:10:43.710
survived and the former
Confederate leaders.

01:10:43.710 --> 01:10:46.920
There were 27 in Jefferson
Davis's government.

01:10:46.920 --> 01:10:50.340
They were now becoming leaders
of the anti-Reconstruction.

01:10:50.340 --> 01:10:52.890
They were becoming mayors
of Atlanta, governors

01:10:52.890 --> 01:10:55.590
of South Carolina, and they
were being welcomed back

01:10:55.590 --> 01:10:58.620
into the fold at
Harvard Law School.

01:10:58.620 --> 01:11:01.500
Now, to do that,
you need to redefine

01:11:01.500 --> 01:11:03.420
what the Civil War is about.

01:11:03.420 --> 01:11:05.160
And one of the
things that we have

01:11:05.160 --> 01:11:06.990
been able to ascertain
through the letters

01:11:06.990 --> 01:11:09.510
and notes of the
students is that everyone

01:11:09.510 --> 01:11:11.850
thought that the war
was about slavery when

01:11:11.850 --> 01:11:13.560
the war was being fought.

01:11:13.560 --> 01:11:17.360
So, it was slavery that
drove the Union students

01:11:17.360 --> 01:11:18.030
to volunteer.

01:11:18.030 --> 01:11:20.430
It was slavery that was the--

01:11:20.430 --> 01:11:23.610
that caused the fights that
went into Harvard Square.

01:11:23.610 --> 01:11:27.570
They emptied the classroom
fighting each other.

01:11:27.570 --> 01:11:29.100
It was slavery.

01:11:29.100 --> 01:11:32.250
Suddenly, it-- after
the war is over,

01:11:32.250 --> 01:11:33.930
it becomes convenient
to redefine

01:11:33.930 --> 01:11:36.690
the war about something else.

01:11:36.690 --> 01:11:40.020
States' rights, theories of
constitutionality, you know,

01:11:40.020 --> 01:11:42.720
now we've resolved
it, so we can move on.

01:11:42.720 --> 01:11:44.790
And let's forget
about segregation.

01:11:44.790 --> 01:11:46.860
Let's forget about racism.

01:11:46.860 --> 01:11:49.540
And I'm afraid that
one of the, on my mind,

01:11:49.540 --> 01:11:51.990
one of the worst chapters
of the history of the school

01:11:51.990 --> 01:11:57.240
was the 20 years under Langdell,
when Langdell essentially

01:11:57.240 --> 01:12:00.321
wrote out racism
and civil rights

01:12:00.321 --> 01:12:01.737
from the curriculum
of the school.

01:12:05.087 --> 01:12:06.920
- Here's a question for
both of us, I guess.

01:12:06.920 --> 01:12:12.488
What are the next steps at the
law school beyond the new seal?

01:12:12.488 --> 01:12:12.988
Well.

01:12:17.810 --> 01:12:18.350
OK.

01:12:18.350 --> 01:12:18.860
All right.

01:12:18.860 --> 01:12:19.610
I'm the moderator.

01:12:19.610 --> 01:12:20.894
I'm not supposed to--

01:12:20.894 --> 01:12:21.878
[LAUGHTER]

01:12:23.360 --> 01:12:26.900
Well, there's still a
lot of student interest

01:12:26.900 --> 01:12:31.850
in bringing about a more
inclusive curriculum, as they

01:12:31.850 --> 01:12:32.990
describe it.

01:12:32.990 --> 01:12:37.130
There are discussions
about that, discussions

01:12:37.130 --> 01:12:41.450
about a diversity of
professors, in terms of the way

01:12:41.450 --> 01:12:43.550
they teach the
kinds of subjects,

01:12:43.550 --> 01:12:47.420
bringing race more
into discussions.

01:12:47.420 --> 01:12:50.480
Very often, in a
contracts case or just

01:12:50.480 --> 01:12:53.120
to make an example of civil
procedure or other things,

01:12:53.120 --> 01:12:55.604
there's a surface,
what the issues are--

01:12:55.604 --> 01:12:57.020
there are surface
issues involved,

01:12:57.020 --> 01:12:59.210
but there are
racial aspects of it

01:12:59.210 --> 01:13:01.835
that student would like to
be brought into the mix.

01:13:01.835 --> 01:13:03.710
It's sort of difficult.
There's some thinking

01:13:03.710 --> 01:13:06.682
it's difficult to talk
about race in classes.

01:13:06.682 --> 01:13:08.390
Some people are
uncomfortable doing that.

01:13:08.390 --> 01:13:12.950
I teach criminal procedure,
which, race, obviously,

01:13:12.950 --> 01:13:15.110
is all-- is shot throughout
the Fourth Amendment

01:13:15.110 --> 01:13:17.300
jurisprudence, and
actual jurisprudence,

01:13:17.300 --> 01:13:19.970
but the actual
practice of policing.

01:13:19.970 --> 01:13:23.510
So, it isn't-- it's not a
difficult thing in my subject

01:13:23.510 --> 01:13:24.260
area.

01:13:24.260 --> 01:13:27.510
But there's much more
talk about pedagogy,

01:13:27.510 --> 01:13:29.426
how to raise these
kinds of issues.

01:13:29.426 --> 01:13:30.800
There's a lot of
things going on.

01:13:30.800 --> 01:13:35.870
I think the shield controversy
sort of came and went,

01:13:35.870 --> 01:13:39.460
but the continuing discussion
about transformation of law

01:13:39.460 --> 01:13:43.680
school is very much there.

01:13:43.680 --> 01:13:46.260
Do you have any
thoughts about, any more

01:13:46.260 --> 01:13:48.060
about what you're seeing?

01:13:48.060 --> 01:13:50.580
- Well I agree with all
of what you just said.

01:13:50.580 --> 01:13:54.250
I mean, the students
yearn for context.

01:13:54.250 --> 01:13:56.130
They-- it's one thing--

01:13:56.130 --> 01:13:57.960
what we have gotten
from Langdell

01:13:57.960 --> 01:14:01.290
is a formal curriculum that's
still remarkably the same

01:14:01.290 --> 01:14:04.260
as it was in the 1880s.

01:14:04.260 --> 01:14:05.270
You know?

01:14:05.270 --> 01:14:09.840
And the legal formalism
stripped context

01:14:09.840 --> 01:14:12.840
from the life of the law.

01:14:12.840 --> 01:14:15.840
And I think the students
yearn to have it brought back.

01:14:15.840 --> 01:14:18.120
And many of our colleagues
are working hard

01:14:18.120 --> 01:14:24.090
on this, this issue to make the
legal doctrines contextualized.

01:14:24.090 --> 01:14:26.700
I also think that the
representation on the faculty

01:14:26.700 --> 01:14:28.160
is important.

01:14:28.160 --> 01:14:30.870
We're approaching 20%
Asian-American enrollment.

01:14:30.870 --> 01:14:33.760
At the moment, there's only one
tenured Asian-American faculty

01:14:33.760 --> 01:14:37.410
out of 91 or 92.

01:14:37.410 --> 01:14:41.160
And I think that the
students want a faculty

01:14:41.160 --> 01:14:44.660
that they can identify with,
that are their role models.

01:14:44.660 --> 01:14:50.910
And that involves gender, but
involves ethnicity and race

01:14:50.910 --> 01:14:51.684
as well.

01:14:51.684 --> 01:14:52.350
- I mean, it's--

01:14:52.350 --> 01:14:54.120
I will say one
word for formalism.

01:14:54.120 --> 01:14:55.860
I mean, part of
the answer to that

01:14:55.860 --> 01:15:00.840
is that there's a concern
on the pushback on sort

01:15:00.840 --> 01:15:04.890
of changing curriculum or
doing things too differently is

01:15:04.890 --> 01:15:10.920
that there's a benefit, at
least first year, to focusing

01:15:10.920 --> 01:15:18.240
on analysis, focusing on law,
understanding law as it exists.

01:15:18.240 --> 01:15:21.450
And certainly context is always
going to be important there,

01:15:21.450 --> 01:15:23.010
but you don't want--

01:15:23.010 --> 01:15:25.080
I mean, I'm channeling
other people.

01:15:25.080 --> 01:15:27.480
You do not want a
strictly politics

01:15:27.480 --> 01:15:30.930
class, where people get to
talk about current events

01:15:30.930 --> 01:15:31.440
or whatever.

01:15:31.440 --> 01:15:36.750
And it's-- that's the
fear, that you go too far.

01:15:36.750 --> 01:15:38.250
And so, what we're
trying to do has

01:15:38.250 --> 01:15:40.530
been to balance the
sort of, the case

01:15:40.530 --> 01:15:45.720
method and the Socratic
method to accommodate

01:15:45.720 --> 01:15:48.840
new understandings and different
perspectives on things.

01:15:48.840 --> 01:15:50.270
And a lot of people
want to do it.

01:15:50.270 --> 01:15:52.890
We have faculty
workshops talking

01:15:52.890 --> 01:15:56.840
about how to teach difficult
courses, State v. Man,

01:15:56.840 --> 01:16:02.790
a very famous court
case involving slavery.

01:16:02.790 --> 01:16:04.740
How do we talk about
these kinds of things?

01:16:04.740 --> 01:16:07.934
And cautionary notes
about it's difficult,

01:16:07.934 --> 01:16:09.600
because there might
be some students who

01:16:09.600 --> 01:16:10.474
are upset about that.

01:16:10.474 --> 01:16:12.150
There is no-- the
difficulty is there's

01:16:12.150 --> 01:16:16.180
no one viewpoint about
all of these things.

01:16:16.180 --> 01:16:20.940
One of the critiques
of this notion

01:16:20.940 --> 01:16:24.060
of my idea of having the
shield as something that

01:16:24.060 --> 01:16:26.550
is sort of a living symbol
is that some people don't

01:16:26.550 --> 01:16:29.490
want to be reminded of that.

01:16:29.490 --> 01:16:32.859
And why should African-Americans
be reminded of that?

01:16:32.859 --> 01:16:34.650
And I have a different
perspective on that,

01:16:34.650 --> 01:16:37.590
but there is no one viewpoint.

01:16:37.590 --> 01:16:39.090
And you have to
consider all of them

01:16:39.090 --> 01:16:40.920
and try to come to
some sort of balance.

01:16:40.920 --> 01:16:43.800
So, it's going to be--
it's an interesting time.

01:16:43.800 --> 01:16:49.050
I mean, it's challenging, but
that's what we're here for,

01:16:49.050 --> 01:16:50.420
to solve problems.

01:16:50.420 --> 01:16:51.930
That's what the law
school is about.

01:16:51.930 --> 01:16:54.210
And I think we're going
to rise to that challenge.

01:16:54.210 --> 01:16:58.240
Did you say, have something--
oh, Alexandra, if you may.

01:16:58.240 --> 01:16:59.030
- Yeah, go ahead.

01:16:59.030 --> 01:17:01.529
- I just wanted to make a quick
comment, just from a student

01:17:01.529 --> 01:17:02.160
perspective.

01:17:02.160 --> 01:17:04.620
I'm now a student at Harvard
for the second time in my life

01:17:04.620 --> 01:17:08.100
and consider myself
very lucky to be one.

01:17:08.100 --> 01:17:10.560
But I do think there is a
desire from students, as well,

01:17:10.560 --> 01:17:15.792
to have kind of like a
mission-driven education.

01:17:15.792 --> 01:17:17.250
Like you go to
Harvard, and there's

01:17:17.250 --> 01:17:21.350
this emphasis on how do
you use your education

01:17:21.350 --> 01:17:23.532
to be good, to better society.

01:17:23.532 --> 01:17:24.990
And I think sometimes
when you move

01:17:24.990 --> 01:17:27.060
from the college to the
professional schools,

01:17:27.060 --> 01:17:30.690
that mission-driven sense
gets a little bit lost.

01:17:30.690 --> 01:17:33.390
And so maybe one
practical way would

01:17:33.390 --> 01:17:36.720
be in our professional
schools to kind of emphasize

01:17:36.720 --> 01:17:38.490
that there is--

01:17:38.490 --> 01:17:41.030
our professional schools are
also mission driven, right?

01:17:41.030 --> 01:17:42.690
Like being at the
business school,

01:17:42.690 --> 01:17:46.540
you should have a sense of
going out there and bettering--

01:17:46.540 --> 01:17:49.300
using your education
to better society.

01:17:49.300 --> 01:17:51.080
So maybe that's another actual--

01:17:51.080 --> 01:17:53.100
- Yeah, I would say
for the law school,

01:17:53.100 --> 01:17:55.050
from the time I was
there, its public service

01:17:55.050 --> 01:17:56.790
has been at the heart of it.

01:17:56.790 --> 01:17:59.190
We have time for
one more comment.

01:17:59.190 --> 01:18:02.970
- Can I make one quick
comment on this issue?

01:18:02.970 --> 01:18:06.300
When you asked me about
what would the memorial look

01:18:06.300 --> 01:18:08.956
like, you know, I was a bit
caught off guard, but the--

01:18:08.956 --> 01:18:10.080
- You thought of something.

01:18:10.080 --> 01:18:10.630
- Yeah.

01:18:10.630 --> 01:18:11.130
It's good.

01:18:11.130 --> 01:18:12.090
I appreciate that.

01:18:12.090 --> 01:18:15.570
But the concept that I'd like
to share with you is this.

01:18:15.570 --> 01:18:20.190
I just took a cursory
research at the Harvard series

01:18:20.190 --> 01:18:22.169
of schools in
terms of their work

01:18:22.169 --> 01:18:24.210
that they are doing with
questions of present day

01:18:24.210 --> 01:18:25.230
slavery.

01:18:25.230 --> 01:18:28.190
And there are many
initiatives happening today,

01:18:28.190 --> 01:18:30.900
at the school of health,
at the Kennedy School

01:18:30.900 --> 01:18:33.000
of Government, the
Harvard Law Review,

01:18:33.000 --> 01:18:35.850
you know, and you
can keep going.

01:18:35.850 --> 01:18:38.079
And this is happening,
as well, in the world.

01:18:38.079 --> 01:18:39.620
There are many
initiatives happening.

01:18:39.620 --> 01:18:42.090
So, one, going to the
question of mission-driven,

01:18:42.090 --> 01:18:47.030
would it be possible to conceive
that this institution may help

01:18:47.030 --> 01:18:51.290
frame a new 21st-century
abolitionism movement,

01:18:51.290 --> 01:18:52.990
or abolitionist movement?

01:18:52.990 --> 01:18:54.890
Help contribute to that?

01:18:54.890 --> 01:18:56.340
What would it look like?

01:18:56.340 --> 01:18:57.710
I have no idea.

01:18:57.710 --> 01:18:58.490
Why?

01:18:58.490 --> 01:19:01.460
Well, there are a lot of
people today in conditions

01:19:01.460 --> 01:19:05.740
that are illegal, but
they are still slavery.

01:19:05.740 --> 01:19:07.880
So, the question to me
is not only the past.

01:19:07.880 --> 01:19:09.590
Yes, the past, of course--

01:19:09.590 --> 01:19:11.790
we need to keep working at it.

01:19:11.790 --> 01:19:13.870
But how do we deal with
our present conditions?

01:19:13.870 --> 01:19:17.110
And that will help
better society today,

01:19:17.110 --> 01:19:18.487
just as an offer.

01:19:18.487 --> 01:19:19.820
- That's a great note to end on.

01:19:19.820 --> 01:19:21.290
Thank you very much Thank you.

